WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.440 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:04.392 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.392 --> 00:00:06.832 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.832 --> 00:00:12.500 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:13.460 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:00:13.460 --> 00:00:18.590 align:middle line:84%
So the topic of today is sieve
theory and the large sieve,

00:00:18.590 --> 00:00:20.900 align:middle line:84%
which was the first
place that I know

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:24.140 align:middle line:84%
of where our proofs like the
proofs that we've been talking

00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:26.660 align:middle line:84%
about appeared, and they
appeared in the context

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:29.270 align:middle line:90%
of analytic number theory.

00:00:29.270 --> 00:00:32.460 align:middle line:84%
So we'll talk about that,
and then if there's time,

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:35.120 align:middle line:84%
I'll try to show you a
really very closely analogous

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:37.820 align:middle line:84%
thing in the context
of real analysis.

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:40.260 align:middle line:90%
And we'll compare them.

00:00:40.260 --> 00:00:40.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:55.580 align:middle line:90%


00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:56.220 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:00:56.220 --> 00:00:57.710 align:middle line:84%
So the setting of
the large sieve

00:00:57.710 --> 00:01:00.770 align:middle line:84%
is that we have a function on
the numbers from 1 up to n.

00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:04.670 align:middle line:84%
So remember that that notation
is the integers from 1 up to n

00:01:04.670 --> 00:01:06.010 align:middle line:90%
And I have a function.

00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:09.840 align:middle line:90%


00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:10.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:13.070 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm going to think
about what happens when

00:01:13.070 --> 00:01:17.610 align:middle line:90%
I reduce these integers mod p.

00:01:17.610 --> 00:01:23.420 align:middle line:90%


00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:26.900 align:middle line:90%
So I'll have pi p of f.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:30.240 align:middle line:84%
That's a function
from Z mod p to C.

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:32.930 align:middle line:90%
And the definition is like this.

00:01:32.930 --> 00:01:38.750 align:middle line:84%
Pi p f of a is defined to
be the sum over all the n

00:01:38.750 --> 00:01:41.670 align:middle line:90%
equal to a mod p of f of a.

00:01:41.670 --> 00:01:47.870 align:middle line:90%


00:01:47.870 --> 00:01:49.310 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:52.860 align:middle line:84%
And the setting of the large
sieve is I have one function f,

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:56.480 align:middle line:84%
but then I consider--
this is a projection of f,

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:02.390 align:middle line:84%
and I consider pi p of f for
many different p's and see what

00:02:02.390 --> 00:02:05.150 align:middle line:84%
the typical behavior and
how the different p's

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:07.755 align:middle line:90%
are related to each other.

00:02:07.755 --> 00:02:08.255 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:08.255 --> 00:02:12.440 align:middle line:90%


00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:13.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:15.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, as before, we've
seen it sometimes helpful

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:18.500 align:middle line:84%
to separate a function
out into its constant part

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:21.260 align:middle line:90%
and its mean zero part.

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:25.190 align:middle line:90%
So f0 would be--

00:02:25.190 --> 00:02:27.090 align:middle line:90%
so take the average value.

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:32.100 align:middle line:84%
So 1 over n, sum n
equals 1 to n, f of n.

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.910 align:middle line:90%
So that's the average value.

00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:39.470 align:middle line:84%
And then maybe still I
still have a function

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:42.440 align:middle line:90%
on numbers from 1 to n to do.

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:43.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:47.400 align:middle line:84%
And then the high part of f
is f minus the constant part.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:53.510 align:middle line:84%
So the sum on n
f high of n is 0.

00:02:53.510 --> 00:02:56.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is a dangerous
notation with the--

00:02:56.590 --> 00:03:01.475 align:middle line:90%
I'll make it a capital H.

00:03:01.475 --> 00:03:01.975 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:01.975 --> 00:03:05.920 align:middle line:84%
And you can do the same
thing with the projections.

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:14.020 align:middle line:84%
So if I take the projection of
f0, it's 1 over p sum a and Z

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:17.303 align:middle line:90%
by p pi pf of a.

00:03:17.303 --> 00:03:18.345 align:middle line:90%
It's a constant function.

00:03:18.345 --> 00:03:23.080 align:middle line:90%


00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:30.740 align:middle line:84%
And pi p of f pi is pi p
of f minus pi p of epsilon.

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:34.220 align:middle line:90%


00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:34.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:36.178 align:middle line:84%
A little tiny
remark, because I was

00:03:36.178 --> 00:03:38.210 align:middle line:84%
careful about where to
put the parentheses,

00:03:38.210 --> 00:03:39.800 align:middle line:90%
but it doesn't actually matter.

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:49.150 align:middle line:84%
So pi p of f pi is the same
thing as pi p of f high.

00:03:49.150 --> 00:03:57.753 align:middle line:84%
And pi p of f0 it's the same
thing as pi p of epsilon.

00:03:57.753 --> 00:03:58.420 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:03:58.420 --> 00:04:00.962 align:middle line:84%
Can you just explain what the
bracket means on the definition

00:04:00.962 --> 00:04:02.712 align:middle line:90%
f0 again?

00:04:02.712 --> 00:04:03.920 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: This one here?

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:04.795 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah, yeah.

00:04:04.795 --> 00:04:08.530 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So f0 is a
function of, let's say m.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:12.490 align:middle line:84%
And inside the large
bracket is a number, which

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:14.303 align:middle line:90%
is like the average value of f.

00:04:14.303 --> 00:04:15.970 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So those
are just parentheses.

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:17.079 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Those
are just parentheses.

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:17.621 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:04:17.621 --> 00:04:26.440 align:middle line:90%


00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:27.490 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:04:27.490 --> 00:04:32.680 align:middle line:84%
So the theme of the large sieve
is that if you take almost

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:35.950 align:middle line:84%
arbitrary function here and
you look at many different

00:04:35.950 --> 00:04:43.420 align:middle line:84%
projections, then the
oscillating part of-- the high

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:45.760 align:middle line:84%
frequency part of the
projections will on average be

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:51.880 align:middle line:84%
pretty small, whereas
the constant part--

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:54.160 align:middle line:84%
well, it only depends on
the constant part of f,

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:57.700 align:middle line:84%
but it could be
typically bigger.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:04:58.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:00.630 align:middle line:84%
So let me write a theorem
which makes that useless.

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:08.412 align:middle line:90%


00:05:08.412 --> 00:05:10.995 align:middle line:84%
I might need just a little more
notation to state our theorem.

00:05:10.995 --> 00:05:17.590 align:middle line:90%


00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:18.310 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:22.840 align:middle line:84%
So let's say capital PM is
the set of prime numbers

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:30.700 align:middle line:84%
p prime in the range M over
2 less than p less than M.

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:36.250 align:middle line:84%
So here is the main theorem,
which was proven by Linnik.

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:42.370 align:middle line:84%
It says that if you have
a function N goes to C

00:05:42.370 --> 00:05:49.840 align:middle line:84%
and we have an M which goes
up to square root of N,

00:05:49.840 --> 00:06:05.770 align:middle line:84%
then if I take the sum p and PM
of pi p of f high L2 squared,

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:11.470 align:middle line:84%
then that is bounded by
N over M times the sum

00:06:11.470 --> 00:06:14.520 align:middle line:90%
on N of f high of n squared.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:19.270 align:middle line:90%


00:06:19.270 --> 00:06:19.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:24.665 align:middle line:90%


00:06:24.665 --> 00:06:28.300 align:middle line:84%
So it takes a little
bit of work to digest

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:30.550 align:middle line:84%
the statement of this theorem
and what kind of a bound

00:06:30.550 --> 00:06:31.610 align:middle line:90%
this is giving us.

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:33.290 align:middle line:90%
So let's digest it together.

00:06:33.290 --> 00:06:36.760 align:middle line:84%
And by doing-- we'll digest
it by doing some applications.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And then after that,
we'll come back

00:06:38.260 --> 00:06:39.468 align:middle line:90%
and we'll prove this theorem.

00:06:39.468 --> 00:06:41.834 align:middle line:90%


00:06:41.834 --> 00:06:42.334 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:42.334 --> 00:06:47.620 align:middle line:90%


00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:50.528 align:middle line:84%
The character in our story is
the primes of size about M,

00:06:50.528 --> 00:06:52.570 align:middle line:84%
and it's useful to know
about how many there are.

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:55.320 align:middle line:84%
So a background fact from
analytic number theory

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:57.420 align:middle line:84%
is that the number
of primes about M

00:06:57.420 --> 00:07:01.860 align:middle line:84%
is around M over log M,
which very roughly I'm just

00:07:01.860 --> 00:07:04.840 align:middle line:90%
going to say is about M.

00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:05.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:08.370 align:middle line:84%
So there are about
M terms in this sum.

00:07:08.370 --> 00:07:13.470 align:middle line:84%
It sometimes is helpful to
replace the sum by an average.

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:23.730 align:middle line:84%
So a corollary is that
the average p and PM

00:07:23.730 --> 00:07:31.350 align:middle line:84%
of pi p of f high L2
squared is less than N

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:36.830 align:middle line:84%
over M squared times the sum
on M of f high of N squared.

00:07:36.830 --> 00:07:43.170 align:middle line:90%


00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:46.074 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:46.074 --> 00:07:48.610 align:middle line:84%
So as a first
application of this,

00:07:48.610 --> 00:07:52.500 align:middle line:90%
let's prove an estimate about--

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:55.210 align:middle line:84%
so last time, I gave the
example of the square numbers.

00:07:55.210 --> 00:07:57.210 align:middle line:84%
The square numbers have
the interesting property

00:07:57.210 --> 00:07:59.910 align:middle line:84%
that if you reduce
the mod p for any p,

00:07:59.910 --> 00:08:02.130 align:middle line:84%
you get the quadratic
residues and there are only

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:04.800 align:middle line:90%
p plus 1 over 2 of them.

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:06.880 align:middle line:84%
So let's think about
a situation like that.

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:09.450 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you have a set, and
when you reduce it modulo p,

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:14.230 align:middle line:84%
you get significantly less than
all p of the residue classes.

00:08:14.230 --> 00:08:15.910 align:middle line:84%
What does that tell
us about the set?

00:08:15.910 --> 00:08:23.940 align:middle line:90%


00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:31.950 align:middle line:84%
So there is a corollary if
N is a subset of 1 to N,

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:36.520 align:middle line:84%
and pi p of A is
significantly smaller than p.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:41.190 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to say it's
less than 0.99 times p.

00:08:41.190 --> 00:08:44.550 align:middle line:84%
Just some constant
that's less than 1.

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:47.980 align:middle line:84%
And for all p would
be interesting,

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:52.065 align:middle line:84%
but I'm going to say for
all the p and PM to the 1/2.

00:08:52.065 --> 00:08:54.690 align:middle line:84%
So we only actually are going to
use the primes of size about N

00:08:54.690 --> 00:08:55.340 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:58.020 align:middle line:90%


00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:03.750 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion is that the
size of A is bounded by around N

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:06.550 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:09.755 align:middle line:84%
This would be the case if was
the set of square numbers.

00:09:09.755 --> 00:09:11.290 align:middle line:84%
If A was the set
of square numbers.

00:09:11.290 --> 00:09:13.180 align:middle line:84%
This would be
basically half of p.

00:09:13.180 --> 00:09:15.390 align:middle line:84%
This would be all the
primes, so in particular

00:09:15.390 --> 00:09:16.690 align:middle line:90%
all of those primes.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:19.800 align:middle line:84%
And this set of square numbers
would have cardinality N

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:20.360 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:22.920 align:middle line:90%


00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:25.345 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:25.345 --> 00:09:31.680 align:middle line:84%
So let's make our function the
characteristic function of A.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:32.315 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:09:32.315 --> 00:09:39.060 align:middle line:90%


00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:39.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:39.950 --> 00:09:53.610 align:middle line:84%
So if I look at the sum A in Z
mod p of pi p f of a squared.

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:59.310 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that p is
in this, PM to the 1/2.

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:01.930 align:middle line:90%
OK, so how big would this be?

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:05.280 align:middle line:84%
Well, if each of these
entries, if each of these guys

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:08.370 align:middle line:84%
were the same as each other,
then the size of this thing

00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:12.630 align:middle line:90%
would be A divided by P.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:14.530 align:middle line:90%
And it would be squared.

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:17.970 align:middle line:90%
And I'd be summing over p terms.

00:10:17.970 --> 00:10:19.800 align:middle line:84%
So if all these
values pi pf of a,

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:21.430 align:middle line:84%
they were all equal
to each other,

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:25.440 align:middle line:84%
they would each have
size size of A over p.

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:27.750 align:middle line:84%
And then the sum
would be like this.

00:10:27.750 --> 00:10:29.680 align:middle line:84%
They could be unequal
to each other,

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:31.710 align:middle line:84%
and then by a
Cauchy-Schwarz argument,

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:33.680 align:middle line:90%
this would be even bigger.

00:10:33.680 --> 00:10:34.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:35.850 align:middle line:84%
And then simplifying
this a little bit,

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:40.650 align:middle line:84%
it's around A squared
N to the minus 1/2.

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:44.010 align:middle line:90%


00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:45.580 align:middle line:84%
Because p is around
N to the 1/2.

00:10:45.580 --> 00:10:48.210 align:middle line:90%


00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:49.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:53.730 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens if
we take the high part?

00:10:53.730 --> 00:11:04.980 align:middle line:84%
Well, because pi
p-- so the support

00:11:04.980 --> 00:11:12.810 align:middle line:84%
of pi p of f that's
contained in pi p of A.

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:22.890 align:middle line:84%
So the size of the support pi p
of f is less than 0.99 times p.

00:11:22.890 --> 00:11:26.070 align:middle line:84%
That's enough to say that this
function is not super close

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:30.120 align:middle line:90%
to a constant function in L2.

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:43.670 align:middle line:84%
So that implies that the sum
a in Zp pi p of f pi squared

00:11:43.670 --> 00:11:45.370 align:middle line:84%
is around the sum
without the high.

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:59.060 align:middle line:90%


00:11:59.060 --> 00:12:02.725 align:middle line:84%
So all of these L2
norms, they're all big.

00:12:02.725 --> 00:12:16.520 align:middle line:90%


00:12:16.520 --> 00:12:18.938 align:middle line:84%
Does that feel
intuitive to people?

00:12:18.938 --> 00:12:20.230 align:middle line:90%
Should we talk about that more?

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:23.490 align:middle line:90%


00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:23.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:23.990 --> 00:12:24.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:24.750 --> 00:12:26.550 align:middle line:90%
So let's call it a lemma.

00:12:26.550 --> 00:12:30.500 align:middle line:90%


00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:35.330 align:middle line:84%
So lemma is that if I have
a function G on Zp to C--

00:12:35.330 --> 00:12:37.080 align:middle line:84%
it's not really important
that this is Zp.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:40.790 align:middle line:90%
It's just a finite set.

00:12:40.790 --> 00:12:49.650 align:middle line:84%
And the support of g has size
significantly less than p.

00:12:49.650 --> 00:12:52.820 align:middle line:90%


00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:58.310 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion is that
the high part of g L2 squared

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:01.180 align:middle line:84%
is around the same
as g L2 squared.

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:11.525 align:middle line:90%


00:13:11.525 --> 00:13:12.025 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:13:12.025 --> 00:13:22.490 align:middle line:90%


00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:23.681 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:23.681 --> 00:13:28.680 align:middle line:90%
So g is g0 plus g high.

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:32.080 align:middle line:84%
And g0 and g high are always
perpendicular to each other.

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:39.260 align:middle line:90%


00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:45.680 align:middle line:90%
So the sum of--

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:55.970 align:middle line:84%
so g L2 squared is around g0
L2 squared is equal to g0 L2

00:13:55.970 --> 00:13:57.865 align:middle line:90%
squared plus g high L2 squared.

00:13:57.865 --> 00:14:02.900 align:middle line:90%


00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:03.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:17.300 align:middle line:90%


00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:18.960 align:middle line:90%
So OK.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:23.900 align:middle line:84%
If g0 L2 squared was much
smaller than g L2 squared,

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:27.650 align:middle line:84%
then clearly g high L2
squared would be bigger.

00:14:27.650 --> 00:14:39.000 align:middle line:84%
So if g0 L2 squared is less
than 1/2 of g L2 squared,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:40.440 align:middle line:90%
then we're done.

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:43.250 align:middle line:90%


00:14:43.250 --> 00:14:44.755 align:middle line:90%
Otherwise, we go the other way.

00:14:44.755 --> 00:14:57.920 align:middle line:90%


00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:06.080 align:middle line:84%
So let's say S is the
support of g complement.

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:11.210 align:middle line:84%
And notice that S is at least
some definite fraction of p.

00:15:11.210 --> 00:15:18.740 align:middle line:84%
And on S, g high is equal
to, I guess negative g0,

00:15:18.740 --> 00:15:26.570 align:middle line:84%
because they have to add up
to 0 because g vanishes on S.

00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:39.130 align:middle line:84%
So we get g high L2 squared
is at least the sum in S

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:42.233 align:middle line:90%
of g0 squared.

00:15:42.233 --> 00:15:44.770 align:middle line:90%


00:15:44.770 --> 00:15:49.360 align:middle line:84%
But since g0 is constant,
this is at least

00:15:49.360 --> 00:15:56.175 align:middle line:84%
S over p times g0 L2 squared,
which is then at least--

00:15:56.175 --> 00:15:58.930 align:middle line:90%


00:15:58.930 --> 00:16:01.910 align:middle line:84%
so S over p is on
the order of 1 and g0

00:16:01.910 --> 00:16:04.335 align:middle line:84%
L2 squared is on the
order of g L2 squared.

00:16:04.335 --> 00:16:09.425 align:middle line:90%


00:16:09.425 --> 00:16:09.925 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:09.925 --> 00:16:15.190 align:middle line:90%


00:16:15.190 --> 00:16:16.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:19.210 align:middle line:84%
So the high part
of this projection

00:16:19.210 --> 00:16:21.640 align:middle line:84%
has an L2 norm that's
comparable to the L2 norm

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:24.430 align:middle line:84%
of the whole projection, which
is at least this big in terms

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:28.330 align:middle line:84%
of the size of A.
But the L2 norm

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:30.370 align:middle line:84%
of the high part
of the projection

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:33.430 align:middle line:84%
shouldn't be too
big by our theorem.

00:16:33.430 --> 00:16:41.620 align:middle line:84%
So the theorem implies that the
average over p PN to the 1/2

00:16:41.620 --> 00:16:49.070 align:middle line:84%
of this same thing is bounded
above by N over M squared.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:52.010 align:middle line:84%
My M is the square root of
N, so this just cancels.

00:16:52.010 --> 00:16:55.690 align:middle line:84%
And then I get the
sum of f of N squared.

00:16:55.690 --> 00:17:12.309 align:middle line:84%
So this would be bounded
above by the size of A. OK.

00:17:12.309 --> 00:17:18.400 align:middle line:84%
So to summarize, this is bounded
by this is bounded by this.

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:24.520 align:middle line:84%
A squared N to the minus 1/2
bounded by A. A is bounded by N

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:25.060 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:50.050 align:middle line:90%


00:17:50.050 --> 00:17:51.780 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or
comments about it?

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:57.850 align:middle line:90%


00:17:57.850 --> 00:17:58.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:58.360 --> 00:17:58.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:58.910 --> 00:18:03.040 align:middle line:84%
So I feel like it's interesting
that it matches the examples

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:04.610 align:middle line:90%
of the square numbers.

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:06.450 align:middle line:90%
It's sharp in that context.

00:18:06.450 --> 00:18:09.460 align:middle line:90%


00:18:09.460 --> 00:18:12.040 align:middle line:84%
But also it would be nice
to discuss more and look

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:16.000 align:middle line:84%
at more examples to try to
get a feel for the numerology

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.360 align:middle line:90%
of the equations.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:19.720 align:middle line:84%
And a helpful
reference point for me

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:22.600 align:middle line:90%
is to look at a random set.

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:24.735 align:middle line:90%
So reference point.

00:18:24.735 --> 00:18:30.710 align:middle line:90%


00:18:30.710 --> 00:18:31.840 align:middle line:90%
A random set.

00:18:31.840 --> 00:18:34.545 align:middle line:90%


00:18:34.545 --> 00:18:35.045 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:35.045 --> 00:18:38.150 align:middle line:84%
So here we're going to take a
subset of the numbers from 1

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:47.630 align:middle line:84%
to N and we include each number
in A with probability 1/2.

00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:50.220 align:middle line:84%
You could also, as an exercise,
play with this probability.

00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:54.755 align:middle line:84%
But let's just talk
about 1/2 independently.

00:18:54.755 --> 00:18:55.255 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:55.255 --> 00:18:59.580 align:middle line:90%


00:18:59.580 --> 00:19:02.493 align:middle line:90%
So what would we expect?

00:19:02.493 --> 00:19:05.420 align:middle line:90%


00:19:05.420 --> 00:19:08.870 align:middle line:84%
Pi p characteristic
function of A.

00:19:08.870 --> 00:19:10.630 align:middle line:84%
How would we expect
this to behave?

00:19:10.630 --> 00:19:13.940 align:middle line:90%


00:19:13.940 --> 00:19:22.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is the number of N from
1 up to N so that N equals A mod

00:19:22.550 --> 00:19:29.200 align:middle line:84%
p and N is in capital A. And
each one of those candidates was

00:19:29.200 --> 00:19:30.760 align:middle line:90%
chosen with probability 1/2.

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:37.870 align:middle line:90%


00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:42.830 align:middle line:84%
So the expected value
over our choice of A.

00:19:42.830 --> 00:19:49.420 align:middle line:84%
So over the random choice of
this set A, of pi p1A little a

00:19:49.420 --> 00:19:52.680 align:middle line:84%
would be half of the
number of guys here.

00:19:52.680 --> 00:20:01.510 align:middle line:90%


00:20:01.510 --> 00:20:05.960 align:middle line:84%
So that's essentially
1/2 of N over p.

00:20:05.960 --> 00:20:10.597 align:middle line:90%


00:20:10.597 --> 00:20:11.097 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:11.097 --> 00:20:13.720 align:middle line:90%


00:20:13.720 --> 00:20:17.590 align:middle line:84%
Well, you wouldn't necessarily
expect this number to be exactly

00:20:17.590 --> 00:20:19.150 align:middle line:90%
N over 2p every time.

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:21.930 align:middle line:84%
We choose randomly, you'll
see some ups and downs.

00:20:21.930 --> 00:20:28.210 align:middle line:90%


00:20:28.210 --> 00:20:32.700 align:middle line:84%
So the standard deviation of
the number that gets picked here

00:20:32.700 --> 00:20:36.990 align:middle line:84%
would be the square root
of the size of this.

00:20:36.990 --> 00:20:45.930 align:middle line:84%
So it also would see that
with high probability,

00:20:45.930 --> 00:20:48.240 align:middle line:84%
the actual size
of the projection

00:20:48.240 --> 00:20:54.300 align:middle line:84%
minus the approximate
size would be bounded

00:20:54.300 --> 00:21:00.365 align:middle line:90%
by the square root of this.

00:21:00.365 --> 00:21:05.580 align:middle line:90%


00:21:05.580 --> 00:21:09.050 align:middle line:84%
And it typically would have
size around this square root.

00:21:09.050 --> 00:21:13.400 align:middle line:90%


00:21:13.400 --> 00:21:22.200 align:middle line:84%
So for example, if p is
in capital PN to the 1/2,

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:26.220 align:middle line:84%
then the actual size of the
projection minus its expected

00:21:26.220 --> 00:21:29.930 align:middle line:84%
size would be
around N to the 1/4.

00:21:29.930 --> 00:21:40.798 align:middle line:90%


00:21:40.798 --> 00:21:41.298 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:41.298 --> 00:21:44.106 align:middle line:90%


00:21:44.106 --> 00:21:50.730 align:middle line:84%
So let's compare this
with what our theorem says

00:21:50.730 --> 00:21:52.100 align:middle line:90%
about an arbitrary set.

00:21:52.100 --> 00:21:56.730 align:middle line:90%


00:21:56.730 --> 00:21:59.670 align:middle line:84%
So what we concluded
is for every P in here

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:05.830 align:middle line:84%
and for every A in Z mod
p, we would have this.

00:22:05.830 --> 00:22:10.920 align:middle line:84%
So if we took a random set
and then for every P and every

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:15.690 align:middle line:84%
A, the difference between the
actual size of the projection

00:22:15.690 --> 00:22:20.790 align:middle line:84%
and its expected size would
be square root of the number

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:25.230 align:middle line:84%
of choices, which would
work out to N to the 1/4.

00:22:25.230 --> 00:22:30.690 align:middle line:84%
We're going to compare this to
what our large sieve tells us

00:22:30.690 --> 00:22:31.930 align:middle line:90%
about an arbitrary set.

00:22:31.930 --> 00:22:34.860 align:middle line:90%


00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:37.400 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about the reference setup?

00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:44.220 align:middle line:90%


00:22:44.220 --> 00:22:45.591 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:45.591 --> 00:22:48.006 align:middle line:90%
So corollary three.

00:22:48.006 --> 00:22:52.582 align:middle line:90%


00:22:52.582 --> 00:22:59.370 align:middle line:84%
If A is any subset
of numbers up to N,

00:22:59.370 --> 00:23:07.200 align:middle line:84%
then if I take the average
over primes of size around N

00:23:07.200 --> 00:23:17.040 align:middle line:84%
to the 1/2, and then I take
the average over A and Z mod p,

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:24.120 align:middle line:84%
I take the actual size pi
p1A of A, and I subtract off

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:33.120 align:middle line:90%
the expected size A over p.

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:37.560 align:middle line:84%
So this is what-- so we
have this many elements

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:38.970 align:middle line:90%
and we reduce them all mod p.

00:23:38.970 --> 00:23:43.380 align:middle line:84%
I would expect, on average,
that this number of them

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:46.380 align:middle line:84%
would be congruent
to little a mod p.

00:23:46.380 --> 00:23:52.820 align:middle line:84%
So then this is bounded by N to
the 1/4 and this matches this.

00:23:52.820 --> 00:23:57.438 align:middle line:90%


00:23:57.438 --> 00:23:57.938 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:57.938 --> 00:24:05.170 align:middle line:90%


00:24:05.170 --> 00:24:10.120 align:middle line:84%
So the proof is copy down
what corollary one tells us.

00:24:10.120 --> 00:24:12.480 align:middle line:90%
It basically tells us this.

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:19.820 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to plug in
corollary one where p is PN,

00:24:19.820 --> 00:24:22.760 align:middle line:90%
where M is N to the 1/2.

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:26.540 align:middle line:90%
That will make this disappear.

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:32.420 align:middle line:84%
And of course, corollary one
tells us that the average p

00:24:32.420 --> 00:24:43.550 align:middle line:84%
and PN to the 1/2 sum A in Z mod
p of pi p1 A of A minus A over p

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:49.740 align:middle line:84%
squared is bounded
by the L2 norm of f,

00:24:49.740 --> 00:24:59.630 align:middle line:90%
which would be the size of A.

00:24:59.630 --> 00:25:01.262 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:01.262 --> 00:25:06.980 align:middle line:84%
And that's smaller than N. Then
if I want to replace this sum

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:13.940 align:middle line:84%
by an average, then I'm
going to divide by p,

00:25:13.940 --> 00:25:16.340 align:middle line:84%
which has size
around N to the 1/2.

00:25:16.340 --> 00:25:18.060 align:middle line:84%
So we replace the
sum by the average,

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:21.110 align:middle line:84%
then this is bounded
by N to the 1/2.

00:25:21.110 --> 00:25:23.190 align:middle line:90%
And there's a square here.

00:25:23.190 --> 00:25:24.810 align:middle line:84%
So I want to get
rid of the square.

00:25:24.810 --> 00:25:27.200 align:middle line:90%
I would use Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:40.345 align:middle line:84%
Get the average on p, average
on A. Get rid of the square.

00:25:40.345 --> 00:25:52.310 align:middle line:90%


00:25:52.310 --> 00:25:54.420 align:middle line:84%
So that's the proof
of the corollary.

00:25:54.420 --> 00:26:05.190 align:middle line:90%


00:26:05.190 --> 00:26:05.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:09.590 align:middle line:90%


00:26:09.590 --> 00:26:12.050 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:26:12.050 --> 00:26:17.630 align:middle line:84%
So the large sieve is telling
us that if you look at a residue

00:26:17.630 --> 00:26:24.320 align:middle line:84%
class with a random p and a
random a, then it behaves--

00:26:24.320 --> 00:26:28.340 align:middle line:84%
so you take an arbitrary set,
a worst case, complicated,

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:29.640 align:middle line:90%
any set at all.

00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:31.970 align:middle line:84%
But then you look at
a random residue class

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:34.220 align:middle line:84%
with a random p and
a random a, then

00:26:34.220 --> 00:26:37.075 align:middle line:84%
it behaves a lot like you
had taken a random set.

00:26:37.075 --> 00:26:41.810 align:middle line:90%


00:26:41.810 --> 00:26:46.230 align:middle line:84%
So a cute application of this
is if A is the set of primes.

00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:48.882 align:middle line:84%
And there's a fun question,
an interesting question

00:26:48.882 --> 00:26:49.590 align:middle line:90%
in number theory.

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:54.650 align:middle line:84%
How many primes are there in
some arithmetic progression?

00:26:54.650 --> 00:26:59.030 align:middle line:90%
So that's exactly this thing.

00:26:59.030 --> 00:27:00.180 align:middle line:90%
A is the set of primes.

00:27:00.180 --> 00:27:02.013 align:middle line:84%
And this is telling us
how many primes there

00:27:02.013 --> 00:27:04.740 align:middle line:84%
are that are congruent
to a modulo little p.

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:12.594 align:middle line:90%


00:27:12.594 --> 00:27:15.110 align:middle line:84%
So the question is,
how evenly distributed

00:27:15.110 --> 00:27:17.450 align:middle line:84%
are the primes among
these different arithmetic

00:27:17.450 --> 00:27:18.530 align:middle line:90%
progressions?

00:27:18.530 --> 00:27:21.800 align:middle line:84%
And the conjecture would
be that for every little p

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:27.710 align:middle line:84%
and every little a that's not
zero, this is always true.

00:27:27.710 --> 00:27:30.650 align:middle line:84%
And this corollary
actually makes

00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:31.890 align:middle line:90%
some progress towards that.

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:34.348 align:middle line:84%
It says we don't know that it's
true for all the little p's

00:27:34.348 --> 00:27:38.330 align:middle line:84%
and all the little a's, but we
know it's true for most of them.

00:27:38.330 --> 00:27:39.860 align:middle line:84%
Now, it's a little
bit silly to call

00:27:39.860 --> 00:27:41.940 align:middle line:84%
that a corollary
about the primes,

00:27:41.940 --> 00:27:43.662 align:middle line:84%
because it uses nothing
about the primes.

00:27:43.662 --> 00:27:46.120 align:middle line:84%
It just uses the fact that the
primes are a set of numbers.

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:51.290 align:middle line:90%


00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:51.900 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:55.340 align:middle line:84%
But that line of
reasoning is actually

00:27:55.340 --> 00:27:59.040 align:middle line:84%
important in some of the things
we know about the questions.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:02.270 align:middle line:84%
How well are primes
distributed modulo p?

00:28:02.270 --> 00:28:04.680 align:middle line:84%
So next class we'll come
back to the question,

00:28:04.680 --> 00:28:07.470 align:middle line:84%
how much do we know
about this function

00:28:07.470 --> 00:28:09.930 align:middle line:90%
when A is the set of primes.

00:28:09.930 --> 00:28:13.150 align:middle line:84%
And we'll do the
Bombieri-Vinogradov theorem,

00:28:13.150 --> 00:28:14.887 align:middle line:84%
which is not quite
the state of the art,

00:28:14.887 --> 00:28:16.470 align:middle line:84%
but for many, many
years was the state

00:28:16.470 --> 00:28:18.290 align:middle line:90%
of the art about this question.

00:28:18.290 --> 00:28:21.330 align:middle line:90%


00:28:21.330 --> 00:28:21.990 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:28:21.990 --> 00:28:24.020 align:middle line:84%
It uses these ideas
in a crucial way.

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:28.380 align:middle line:90%


00:28:28.380 --> 00:28:29.520 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:28:29.520 --> 00:28:30.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:30.190 --> 00:28:33.930 align:middle line:84%
So that was my survey of some
applications of this large sieve

00:28:33.930 --> 00:28:34.840 align:middle line:90%
inequality.

00:28:34.840 --> 00:28:38.075 align:middle line:84%
And next we'll prove the
large sieve inequality itself.

00:28:38.075 --> 00:28:45.280 align:middle line:90%


00:28:45.280 --> 00:28:45.780 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:47.790 align:middle line:84%
Actually, there was one
other thing I wanted to say.

00:28:47.790 --> 00:28:48.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:48.290 --> 00:28:52.890 align:middle line:84%
So imagine that A was
a set of size N over 2.

00:28:52.890 --> 00:29:01.960 align:middle line:84%
Then this thing here would
have size about N over p,

00:29:01.960 --> 00:29:04.370 align:middle line:84%
which works out to
about N to the 1/2,

00:29:04.370 --> 00:29:07.540 align:middle line:84%
and this thing has size
about N to the 1/2.

00:29:07.540 --> 00:29:09.850 align:middle line:84%
And the error is
about N to the 1/4.

00:29:09.850 --> 00:29:14.980 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is
the pi p of f sub 0.

00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:22.390 align:middle line:84%
And so what we're seeing
here is that the pi p of f0

00:29:22.390 --> 00:29:27.830 align:middle line:84%
is much larger than pi p of
f high at most of the points.

00:29:27.830 --> 00:29:29.740 align:middle line:90%
So say in L2.

00:29:29.740 --> 00:29:32.920 align:middle line:84%
So when we take a set
of size N over 2 and we

00:29:32.920 --> 00:29:34.820 align:middle line:84%
look at all these
different projections.

00:29:34.820 --> 00:29:37.430 align:middle line:84%
A typical projection
looks almost constant.

00:29:37.430 --> 00:29:41.650 align:middle line:84%
It's a constant function plus
something that's much smaller.

00:29:41.650 --> 00:29:44.470 align:middle line:84%
So this process of
taking a random function

00:29:44.470 --> 00:29:47.030 align:middle line:90%
takes a set with no structure.

00:29:47.030 --> 00:29:49.815 align:middle line:84%
And it produces something
that's almost constant.

00:29:49.815 --> 00:29:51.190 align:middle line:84%
And people sometimes
use the word

00:29:51.190 --> 00:29:53.810 align:middle line:84%
that the projections
are getting smoother.

00:29:53.810 --> 00:29:56.020 align:middle line:84%
And when we do the real
analysis version a little bit

00:29:56.020 --> 00:29:59.110 align:middle line:84%
later in class, we'll see
that smoother is exactly

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:00.015 align:middle line:90%
the right word.

00:30:00.015 --> 00:30:04.780 align:middle line:90%


00:30:04.780 --> 00:30:05.800 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:07.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:07.010 --> 00:30:07.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:07.510 --> 00:30:09.100 align:middle line:84%
So I think that's a good
way to summarize what

00:30:09.100 --> 00:30:10.580 align:middle line:90%
the large sieve is telling us.

00:30:10.580 --> 00:30:12.130 align:middle line:84%
It says if we take
a set A, which

00:30:12.130 --> 00:30:14.860 align:middle line:84%
is a pretty decent fraction
of the numbers from 1 to n,

00:30:14.860 --> 00:30:17.180 align:middle line:84%
and then when we look at
all the projections of it,

00:30:17.180 --> 00:30:21.340 align:middle line:84%
most of those projections
are almost constant.

00:30:21.340 --> 00:30:23.470 align:middle line:84%
And that's relevant
for this question

00:30:23.470 --> 00:30:29.440 align:middle line:84%
up here, because if we
hypothesize that pi sub p of A

00:30:29.440 --> 00:30:32.710 align:middle line:84%
has size smaller than 0.99
of p, that's telling us

00:30:32.710 --> 00:30:36.340 align:middle line:84%
the projection is really
not very constant.

00:30:36.340 --> 00:30:38.510 align:middle line:84%
That's only possible
for small sets.

00:30:38.510 --> 00:30:40.910 align:middle line:84%
So that's where we get that
upper bound on the size of A.

00:30:40.910 --> 00:30:42.400 align:middle line:84%
If A was bigger
than that, then it

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:45.460 align:middle line:84%
would start to be the case
that the projections of a

00:30:45.460 --> 00:30:47.620 align:middle line:84%
would look pretty
constant, and it would

00:30:47.620 --> 00:30:50.560 align:middle line:84%
then it would be impossible that
the support would be that small.

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:51.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:59.200 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What does p tilde
capital P N to the 1/2 mean?

00:30:59.200 --> 00:31:01.870 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: What does--

00:31:01.870 --> 00:31:04.930 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Under the average.

00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:05.950 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: This one?

00:31:05.950 --> 00:31:06.830 align:middle line:90%
Oh, sorry.

00:31:06.830 --> 00:31:08.560 align:middle line:90%
That's P in.

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:11.800 align:middle line:84%
So capital P N to the 1/2 is the
set of primes of size about N

00:31:11.800 --> 00:31:12.775 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:31:12.775 --> 00:31:14.450 align:middle line:90%
This prime is one of them.

00:31:14.450 --> 00:31:14.950 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:14.950 --> 00:31:15.870 align:middle line:90%
Thanks for-- thanks.

00:31:15.870 --> 00:31:21.460 align:middle line:90%


00:31:21.460 --> 00:31:23.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:23.470 --> 00:31:27.540 align:middle line:84%
OK, so next, let's
prove Linnik's theorem.

00:31:27.540 --> 00:31:39.940 align:middle line:90%


00:31:39.940 --> 00:31:41.680 align:middle line:84%
So the proof of
Linnik's theorem is

00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:44.000 align:middle line:90%
based on the Fourier transform.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.180 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to take the
Fourier transform of all

00:31:46.180 --> 00:31:47.800 align:middle line:84%
of these characters,
and then we're

00:31:47.800 --> 00:31:50.008 align:middle line:84%
going to see how the different
Fourier transforms are

00:31:50.008 --> 00:31:52.780 align:middle line:90%
related to each other.

00:31:52.780 --> 00:31:56.320 align:middle line:84%
So first let me remind you how
the Fourier transform works

00:31:56.320 --> 00:32:02.800 align:middle line:84%
for functions on the integers
and functions on Z mod p.

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:05.200 align:middle line:90%
So f is going to be--

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:07.630 align:middle line:84%
think of it as a function
on the integers, which

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:12.460 align:middle line:84%
is supported in
this set 1 up to N.

00:32:12.460 --> 00:32:15.800 align:middle line:84%
And so if I take its Fourier
transform, what does that mean?

00:32:15.800 --> 00:32:19.720 align:middle line:84%
The Fourier transform is going
to be a function on R mod Z,

00:32:19.720 --> 00:32:26.980 align:middle line:84%
and it's defined by f hat
of Z is the sum on n f of n,

00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:31.510 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus 2
pi i ksi dot ksi.

00:32:31.510 --> 00:32:33.050 align:middle line:90%
That's the Fourier transform.

00:32:33.050 --> 00:32:35.720 align:middle line:84%
And it has a Fourier inversion
and it has a Plancherel.

00:32:35.720 --> 00:32:38.200 align:middle line:90%
And they go like this.

00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:44.680 align:middle line:84%
Fourier inversion that
tells us that f of n

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:49.675 align:middle line:84%
is the integral from
0 to 1, f hat of ksi,

00:32:49.675 --> 00:32:53.740 align:middle line:90%
e to the 2 pi i ksi n d ksi.

00:32:53.740 --> 00:32:58.530 align:middle line:84%
And there's a Plancherel,
and it tells us

00:32:58.530 --> 00:33:02.190 align:middle line:84%
that the sum on n
of f of n squared

00:33:02.190 --> 00:33:07.060 align:middle line:84%
is the integral from 0 to 1
norm of f hat ksi squared d ksi.

00:33:07.060 --> 00:33:10.600 align:middle line:90%


00:33:10.600 --> 00:33:11.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:11.100 --> 00:33:13.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is probably the most
familiar backwards from the way

00:33:13.590 --> 00:33:14.260 align:middle line:90%
I've written it.

00:33:14.260 --> 00:33:17.290 align:middle line:84%
If you started with a function
on R mod Z, a periodic function,

00:33:17.290 --> 00:33:19.150 align:middle line:84%
you would take its
Fourier series.

00:33:19.150 --> 00:33:21.790 align:middle line:84%
And if you sum the Fourier
series you get the function.

00:33:21.790 --> 00:33:23.200 align:middle line:90%
This is the same thing.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:24.990 align:middle line:84%
We've just chosen
to label the Fourier

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:31.500 align:middle line:84%
series by f and the function
on the circle by f hat.

00:33:31.500 --> 00:33:32.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:32.500 --> 00:33:38.200 align:middle line:84%
And then we will also have
a function on Z mod p.

00:33:38.200 --> 00:33:42.720 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have a function
Z mod p goes to C. Then

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:46.830 align:middle line:84%
its Fourier transform will also
be a function Z mod p goes to C.

00:33:46.830 --> 00:33:51.130 align:middle line:84%
And the definition
is g hat of alpha.

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:54.360 align:middle line:84%
So I'll say that this variable
is called a and this variable

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:55.800 align:middle line:90%
is called alpha.

00:33:55.800 --> 00:33:59.370 align:middle line:84%
So g hat of alpha
will be the sum a in

00:33:59.370 --> 00:34:07.710 align:middle line:84%
Z mod p, g of a, e to the
minus 2 pi i a alpha over p.

00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:12.750 align:middle line:84%
And then we have Fourier
inversion, which tells us

00:34:12.750 --> 00:34:17.460 align:middle line:84%
that g of a can be recovered
as 1 over p sum alpha

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:26.301 align:middle line:84%
in Z mod p, g hat of alpha,
e to the pi i a alpha over p.

00:34:26.301 --> 00:34:29.340 align:middle line:90%
And Plancherel.

00:34:29.340 --> 00:34:33.780 align:middle line:84%
That tells us that the sum
on a, norm of g of a squared

00:34:33.780 --> 00:34:37.469 align:middle line:84%
is 1 over p times
the sum on alpha norm

00:34:37.469 --> 00:34:38.599 align:middle line:90%
of g hat of alpha squared.

00:34:38.599 --> 00:34:42.360 align:middle line:90%


00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:43.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:43.180 --> 00:34:44.880 align:middle line:84%
So that's how the
Fourier transforms

00:34:44.880 --> 00:34:48.090 align:middle line:90%
works for each of these worlds.

00:34:48.090 --> 00:34:49.810 align:middle line:84%
And now we're going
to put it together.

00:34:49.810 --> 00:34:51.810 align:middle line:84%
So if I start with a
function on the integers,

00:34:51.810 --> 00:34:54.960 align:middle line:84%
I reduce it mod p to get
a function on Z mod p.

00:34:54.960 --> 00:34:56.969 align:middle line:84%
How does this Fourier
transform relate

00:34:56.969 --> 00:34:59.080 align:middle line:90%
to this Fourier transform?

00:34:59.080 --> 00:34:59.580 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:59.580 --> 00:35:35.715 align:middle line:90%


00:35:35.715 --> 00:35:36.215 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:36.215 --> 00:35:38.940 align:middle line:90%


00:35:38.940 --> 00:35:42.436 align:middle line:84%
So lemma, I'll call
this lemma dictionary.

00:35:42.436 --> 00:35:46.250 align:middle line:90%


00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:48.750 align:middle line:84%
This is a dictionary between
the integer world and the mod p

00:35:48.750 --> 00:35:49.830 align:middle line:90%
world.

00:35:49.830 --> 00:35:55.710 align:middle line:84%
And it says that if I take
pi p of f hat of alpha,

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:58.660 align:middle line:90%
it is f hat of alpha over p.

00:35:58.660 --> 00:36:03.120 align:middle line:90%


00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:03.800 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:03.800 --> 00:36:06.750 align:middle line:84%
The proof is just
unwinding the definitions

00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:08.560 align:middle line:84%
of what all these
Fourier transforms mean.

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:11.640 align:middle line:84%
So what does it mean,
pi p f hat of alpha?

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:14.340 align:middle line:90%
Pi p f hat of alpha.

00:36:14.340 --> 00:36:21.500 align:middle line:84%
That's the sum a in
Z mod p, pi pf of a,

00:36:21.500 --> 00:36:27.700 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus 2 pi
i, a alpha over p.

00:36:27.700 --> 00:36:28.200 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:30.045 align:middle line:90%
Now who is pi p f of a?

00:36:30.045 --> 00:36:33.216 align:middle line:90%


00:36:33.216 --> 00:36:37.630 align:middle line:84%
Sum a and Z mod p,
open parentheses.

00:36:37.630 --> 00:36:44.400 align:middle line:90%
Sum n equals a mod p of f of n.

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:49.090 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus 2 pi
i a alpha over p.

00:36:49.090 --> 00:36:54.210 align:middle line:90%


00:36:54.210 --> 00:36:54.790 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:54.790 --> 00:36:57.810 align:middle line:84%
Now if you look at
this double sum,

00:36:57.810 --> 00:36:59.720 align:middle line:84%
we're just summing
over all the n's.

00:36:59.720 --> 00:37:03.390 align:middle line:90%


00:37:03.390 --> 00:37:06.570 align:middle line:84%
And now let's look at the
thing that we're summing.

00:37:06.570 --> 00:37:12.930 align:middle line:90%
So n equals a mod p.

00:37:12.930 --> 00:37:19.380 align:middle line:84%
That tells us that e to the
minus 2 pi i n alpha over p

00:37:19.380 --> 00:37:26.822 align:middle line:84%
is the same as e to the
minus 2 pi i a alpha over p.

00:37:26.822 --> 00:37:27.450 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:37:27.450 --> 00:37:29.970 align:middle line:84%
Different n's that are
congruent to a mod p.

00:37:29.970 --> 00:37:34.380 align:middle line:84%
So I think of adding a
multiple of p to this n.

00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:37.930 align:middle line:84%
That multiple of p-- the
p cancels with that p,

00:37:37.930 --> 00:37:40.320 align:middle line:84%
so we're changing
this by an integer,

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:44.430 align:middle line:84%
and it doesn't change
the value of it.

00:37:44.430 --> 00:37:46.302 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:46.302 --> 00:37:51.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is just the
sum over n, f of n,

00:37:51.110 --> 00:37:55.140 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus 2 pi
i n alpha over p.

00:37:55.140 --> 00:38:02.295 align:middle line:90%


00:38:02.295 --> 00:38:02.795 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:02.795 --> 00:38:07.010 align:middle line:90%


00:38:07.010 --> 00:38:08.400 align:middle line:90%
Another little remark.

00:38:08.400 --> 00:38:10.770 align:middle line:84%
This is something we
basically saw last time,

00:38:10.770 --> 00:38:15.650 align:middle line:84%
that if you take the high part
of pi p of f and its L2 norm

00:38:15.650 --> 00:38:18.140 align:middle line:84%
squared, you take the high
part of it, what it means

00:38:18.140 --> 00:38:21.470 align:middle line:84%
is that we removed
the zero frequency.

00:38:21.470 --> 00:38:24.720 align:middle line:84%
So I guess I'll also
call this a lemma,

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:27.340 align:middle line:84%
but it's very similar to
things we've already proved.

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:31.010 align:middle line:90%


00:38:31.010 --> 00:38:40.075 align:middle line:84%
So pi p f pi L2 squared is the
sum on the non-zero alphas.

00:38:40.075 --> 00:38:55.610 align:middle line:90%


00:38:55.610 --> 00:38:57.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:57.560 --> 00:38:59.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:59.870 --> 00:39:05.250 align:middle line:84%
So now we have a
way of writing--

00:39:05.250 --> 00:39:07.430 align:middle line:84%
so let's look at the
theorem we want to prove.

00:39:07.430 --> 00:39:10.880 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take a sum over
different p's of the L2 norms

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:13.510 align:middle line:90%
of the high parts of pi p of f.

00:39:13.510 --> 00:39:14.010 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:39:14.010 --> 00:39:17.270 align:middle line:84%
These lemmas give us a way of
writing that and translating it

00:39:17.270 --> 00:39:22.405 align:middle line:84%
into a sum that involves the
Fourier transform of F. Right.

00:39:22.405 --> 00:39:25.260 align:middle line:90%


00:39:25.260 --> 00:39:25.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:28.880 align:middle line:90%


00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:29.490 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:39:29.490 --> 00:39:31.165 align:middle line:90%
I guess one last remark is.

00:39:31.165 --> 00:39:34.370 align:middle line:90%


00:39:34.370 --> 00:39:40.410 align:middle line:84%
So pi p of f hat of alpha
is f hat of alpha over p.

00:39:40.410 --> 00:39:42.300 align:middle line:90%
That's for any function f.

00:39:42.300 --> 00:39:47.360 align:middle line:84%
And so if I were to take pi
p of f high hat of alpha,

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:50.580 align:middle line:84%
that would be f
high hat alpha of p.

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:56.870 align:middle line:90%


00:39:56.870 --> 00:40:01.940 align:middle line:84%
So now let's write out the left
hand side of Linnik's theorem

00:40:01.940 --> 00:40:03.330 align:middle line:90%
using the Fourier transform.

00:40:03.330 --> 00:40:20.076 align:middle line:90%


00:40:20.076 --> 00:40:20.576 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:20.576 --> 00:40:23.312 align:middle line:90%


00:40:23.312 --> 00:40:28.850 align:middle line:84%
So the left-hand side of our
theorem, I'll just copy it.

00:40:28.850 --> 00:40:39.985 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum p in primes of size
M. Pi p of f, pi hat L2 squared.

00:40:39.985 --> 00:40:45.650 align:middle line:90%


00:40:45.650 --> 00:40:47.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:47.330 --> 00:40:56.780 align:middle line:84%
So that's now some p in PM, some
on the non-zero alpha in Zp.

00:40:56.780 --> 00:40:59.510 align:middle line:90%


00:40:59.510 --> 00:41:03.850 align:middle line:84%
Pi p of f high hat
of alpha squared.

00:41:03.850 --> 00:41:07.070 align:middle line:90%


00:41:07.070 --> 00:41:14.600 align:middle line:84%
Which is equal to sum p in
PM, sum alpha not equal to 0,

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:21.120 align:middle line:84%
and Zp of f high
hat of alpha over p.

00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:24.590 align:middle line:90%


00:41:24.590 --> 00:41:25.260 align:middle line:90%
Norm squared.

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:30.400 align:middle line:90%


00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:30.900 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:41:30.900 --> 00:41:39.190 align:middle line:90%


00:41:39.190 --> 00:41:40.330 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:41.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:44.440 align:middle line:84%
So we're taking the Fourier
transform of the high part of f

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:47.830 align:middle line:84%
and evaluating it at a
set of points norm squared

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:49.960 align:middle line:90%
and adding them all up.

00:41:49.960 --> 00:41:52.840 align:middle line:84%
Let's visualize
that set of points.

00:41:52.840 --> 00:42:00.160 align:middle line:84%
So let's say QM is the
set of alpha over p,

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:03.430 align:middle line:84%
where p is a prime
of size around M,

00:42:03.430 --> 00:42:08.530 align:middle line:84%
and alpha is strictly positive
and less than or equal

00:42:08.530 --> 00:42:09.450 align:middle line:90%
to p minus 1.

00:42:09.450 --> 00:42:18.340 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.340 --> 00:42:19.531 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:19.531 --> 00:42:25.570 align:middle line:84%
So the size of QM is
roughly M squared.

00:42:25.570 --> 00:42:27.790 align:middle line:84%
So we mentioned before
how many choices are there

00:42:27.790 --> 00:42:28.880 align:middle line:90%
for this prime p.

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:31.120 align:middle line:84%
It's about M over log
M, which is roughly

00:42:31.120 --> 00:42:34.600 align:middle line:84%
M. And then for each
prime, we're basically

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:38.290 align:middle line:84%
p choices of alpha,
which is also around M,

00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:43.270 align:middle line:84%
roughly M squared
of these quotients.

00:42:43.270 --> 00:42:45.340 align:middle line:84%
And an important fact
about these quotients

00:42:45.340 --> 00:42:48.500 align:middle line:84%
is that they're distributed
quite evenly on the real line.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:50.240 align:middle line:84%
So there are about
M squared of them,

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:54.070 align:middle line:84%
and the distance between any two
of them is at least M squared.

00:42:54.070 --> 00:42:55.680 align:middle line:90%
So here's a lemma.

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:58.360 align:middle line:90%


00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:04.540 align:middle line:84%
If alpha 1 over P1 and
alpha 2 over P2 are in QM

00:43:04.540 --> 00:43:07.690 align:middle line:84%
and they're not
equal to each other,

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:16.930 align:middle line:84%
then the distance between them
is at least 1 over M squared.

00:43:16.930 --> 00:43:17.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:19.150 align:middle line:90%
Proof.

00:43:19.150 --> 00:43:24.100 align:middle line:84%
We're just going to put it
over a common denominator.

00:43:24.100 --> 00:43:29.770 align:middle line:84%
Alpha 1 over P1
minus alpha 2 over P2

00:43:29.770 --> 00:43:35.130 align:middle line:84%
is alpha 1, P2 minus
alpha 2, P2 over P1P2.

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:39.730 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:43.600 align:middle line:84%
By assumption, the
difference is not zero,

00:43:43.600 --> 00:43:48.220 align:middle line:84%
and so this numerator
is not zero.

00:43:48.220 --> 00:43:50.385 align:middle line:84%
It's an integer, so it
has norm at least one.

00:43:50.385 --> 00:43:53.470 align:middle line:90%


00:43:53.470 --> 00:43:54.900 align:middle line:90%
So it's at least that big.

00:43:54.900 --> 00:43:59.560 align:middle line:90%


00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:01.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:01.750 --> 00:44:03.580 align:middle line:84%
I guess to be
careful I should also

00:44:03.580 --> 00:44:07.540 align:middle line:84%
say that if P1 is
different from P2,

00:44:07.540 --> 00:44:11.320 align:middle line:84%
then these two are never
equal to each other.

00:44:11.320 --> 00:44:14.050 align:middle line:84%
So we never-- so the importance
of making these primes

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:18.670 align:middle line:84%
is that we never have
the same number written

00:44:18.670 --> 00:44:21.790 align:middle line:84%
as a fraction in two
different ways here.

00:44:21.790 --> 00:44:32.020 align:middle line:84%
So that's also make the
remark that if alpha 1 over P1

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:37.690 align:middle line:84%
equals alpha 2 over
P2 in QM, then it

00:44:37.690 --> 00:44:41.730 align:middle line:84%
must be that alpha 1 equals
alpha 2 and P1 equals P2.

00:44:41.730 --> 00:44:47.120 align:middle line:90%


00:44:47.120 --> 00:44:47.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:51.210 align:middle line:90%


00:44:51.210 --> 00:44:51.710 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:44:51.710 --> 00:45:04.990 align:middle line:90%


00:45:04.990 --> 00:45:07.420 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:45:07.420 --> 00:45:09.610 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to erase
the dictionary lemma

00:45:09.610 --> 00:45:12.690 align:middle line:84%
and I'll make a picture of this
set and of what we're doing.

00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:31.720 align:middle line:90%


00:45:31.720 --> 00:45:33.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:33.790 --> 00:45:34.500 align:middle line:90%
Here's a picture.

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:37.360 align:middle line:90%


00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:40.610 align:middle line:90%
So here's a line from 0 to 1.

00:45:40.610 --> 00:45:45.160 align:middle line:84%
And on this line we
have this set, Q sub M,

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:48.160 align:middle line:84%
which is maybe not quite
that evenly spaced,

00:45:48.160 --> 00:45:49.760 align:middle line:90%
but it's quite evenly spaced.

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:52.820 align:middle line:90%
So that's Q sub M. OK.

00:45:52.820 --> 00:45:57.030 align:middle line:90%
And then we're interested in--

00:45:57.030 --> 00:45:59.650 align:middle line:84%
our formula involves
the norm of squared

00:45:59.650 --> 00:46:01.500 align:middle line:90%
of the Fourier transform of f.

00:46:01.500 --> 00:46:08.050 align:middle line:90%


00:46:08.050 --> 00:46:09.443 align:middle line:90%
Let me put that on this axis.

00:46:09.443 --> 00:46:16.120 align:middle line:90%


00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:19.072 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:19.072 --> 00:46:24.210 align:middle line:84%
So this will look
however it looks.

00:46:24.210 --> 00:46:24.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:24.710 --> 00:46:26.400 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about this
a little bit more.

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:30.900 align:middle line:90%


00:46:30.900 --> 00:46:33.150 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:33.150 --> 00:46:39.510 align:middle line:84%
So what we're taking
in that sum is

00:46:39.510 --> 00:46:43.630 align:middle line:84%
we're finding the actual
values at these points

00:46:43.630 --> 00:46:44.945 align:middle line:90%
and we're adding them up.

00:46:44.945 --> 00:46:49.845 align:middle line:90%


00:46:49.845 --> 00:46:52.080 align:middle line:84%
And this sum might
remind you a little bit

00:46:52.080 --> 00:46:55.560 align:middle line:84%
of a Riemann sum that would
help to give an approximation

00:46:55.560 --> 00:46:58.170 align:middle line:90%
of this integral.

00:46:58.170 --> 00:46:59.850 align:middle line:84%
And indeed we're
going to compare

00:46:59.850 --> 00:47:01.265 align:middle line:90%
this sum to this integral.

00:47:01.265 --> 00:47:05.210 align:middle line:90%


00:47:05.210 --> 00:47:05.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:05.710 --> 00:47:08.820 align:middle line:84%
Now there is a way
that the sum could

00:47:08.820 --> 00:47:12.120 align:middle line:84%
be a lot bigger than
the integral, which

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:14.430 align:middle line:90%
is a narrow peak like this.

00:47:14.430 --> 00:47:17.200 align:middle line:84%
If the function is very
big at this one point,

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:19.360 align:middle line:84%
but the peak is
extremely narrow,

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:21.700 align:middle line:84%
then it wouldn't contribute
much to the integral,

00:47:21.700 --> 00:47:23.880 align:middle line:84%
but it's still there
as part of our sum.

00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:29.190 align:middle line:84%
So it's important to know how
narrow a peak like this can be.

00:47:29.190 --> 00:47:32.670 align:middle line:84%
And the heuristic, which
is similar to heuristic

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:36.450 align:middle line:84%
we've talked about before,
is that the function

00:47:36.450 --> 00:47:43.200 align:middle line:84%
f high hat of ksi is roughly
constant on intervals

00:47:43.200 --> 00:47:44.450 align:middle line:90%
of length 1 over n.

00:47:44.450 --> 00:47:49.350 align:middle line:90%


00:47:49.350 --> 00:47:52.110 align:middle line:84%
Because remember that f is
supported on the numbers

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:55.020 align:middle line:90%
from 1 to n.

00:47:55.020 --> 00:47:57.960 align:middle line:84%
So we'll make this
precise in a moment.

00:47:57.960 --> 00:48:00.960 align:middle line:84%
So I'll draw in what it means,
that this peak here should

00:48:00.960 --> 00:48:04.770 align:middle line:90%
have width at least 1 over n.

00:48:04.770 --> 00:48:11.010 align:middle line:84%
And I'll also make a remark that
M is less than or equal to N

00:48:11.010 --> 00:48:12.190 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:48:12.190 --> 00:48:16.860 align:middle line:84%
That's one of the hypotheses
in Linnik's theorem.

00:48:16.860 --> 00:48:21.390 align:middle line:84%
And so that guarantees
that the spacing

00:48:21.390 --> 00:48:27.630 align:middle line:84%
between consecutive points of QM
is smaller than this 1 over N.

00:48:27.630 --> 00:48:31.350 align:middle line:84%
So the picture is right
that this 1 over N

00:48:31.350 --> 00:48:33.900 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than the distance
between the different points

00:48:33.900 --> 00:48:40.270 align:middle line:84%
of Q. So this is
just a heuristic,

00:48:40.270 --> 00:48:41.603 align:middle line:90%
but let's follow it for now.

00:48:41.603 --> 00:48:43.770 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see that it
basically gives the inequality

00:48:43.770 --> 00:48:44.470 align:middle line:90%
that we want.

00:48:44.470 --> 00:48:48.630 align:middle line:84%
And then we can come back
and prove things rigorously.

00:48:48.630 --> 00:48:49.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:49.180 --> 00:49:05.160 align:middle line:84%
So the heuristic tells us that
the sum ksi in QM f high hat

00:49:05.160 --> 00:49:19.340 align:middle line:84%
ksi squared is bounded by N
times the integral from 0 to 1

00:49:19.340 --> 00:49:21.125 align:middle line:90%
f hat high ksi squared.

00:49:21.125 --> 00:49:24.060 align:middle line:90%


00:49:24.060 --> 00:49:25.110 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:49:25.110 --> 00:49:29.430 align:middle line:84%
So take one term of this
sum, say from this point.

00:49:29.430 --> 00:49:35.160 align:middle line:84%
That one term is bounded
by N times the integral

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:38.580 align:middle line:84%
on this interval
around here of width 1

00:49:38.580 --> 00:49:42.485 align:middle line:84%
over N, which is a
piece of this integral.

00:49:42.485 --> 00:49:58.600 align:middle line:90%


00:49:58.600 --> 00:49:59.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:59.100 --> 00:50:17.685 align:middle line:90%


00:50:17.685 --> 00:50:18.185 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:18.185 --> 00:50:18.685 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:50:18.685 --> 00:50:20.730 align:middle line:90%
So the rest is just algebra.

00:50:20.730 --> 00:50:23.930 align:middle line:84%
It's a little bit annoying to
get all of the constants right

00:50:23.930 --> 00:50:26.000 align:middle line:84%
in the algebra,
all the exponents.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:28.495 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, I have already
mastered up a little bit.

00:50:28.495 --> 00:50:34.640 align:middle line:90%


00:50:34.640 --> 00:50:39.470 align:middle line:84%
So if we go back here, the
left-hand side of the theorem

00:50:39.470 --> 00:50:40.800 align:middle line:90%
is indeed this sum.

00:50:40.800 --> 00:50:44.180 align:middle line:84%
I would just copy
that correctly.

00:50:44.180 --> 00:50:48.740 align:middle line:84%
And then for the sum,
I did Plancherel.

00:50:48.740 --> 00:50:50.910 align:middle line:84%
But when you do
Plancherel mod p,

00:50:50.910 --> 00:50:54.540 align:middle line:84%
there's this factor of 1 over
p that I forget frequently.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:50:57.260 align:middle line:90%
So there's a 1 over p there.

00:50:57.260 --> 00:51:00.830 align:middle line:84%
Now the 1 over p, the
p has size about M.

00:51:00.830 --> 00:51:05.745 align:middle line:84%
This is around 1
over M times that.

00:51:05.745 --> 00:51:06.245 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:06.245 --> 00:51:13.070 align:middle line:90%


00:51:13.070 --> 00:51:13.980 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:51:13.980 --> 00:51:18.620 align:middle line:84%
So the left-hand
side of the theorem

00:51:18.620 --> 00:51:23.970 align:middle line:84%
is actually around 1 over
M times this sum over here.

00:51:23.970 --> 00:51:27.835 align:middle line:84%
So that would be bounded by
N over M times this integral.

00:51:27.835 --> 00:51:32.420 align:middle line:90%


00:51:32.420 --> 00:51:34.650 align:middle line:84%
And then we use
Plancherel again,

00:51:34.650 --> 00:51:37.320 align:middle line:84%
and this time there's no factor
that I have trouble remembering.

00:51:37.320 --> 00:51:43.480 align:middle line:84%
So that's N over M sum
on N f high of N squared.

00:51:43.480 --> 00:51:46.500 align:middle line:90%


00:51:46.500 --> 00:51:47.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.165 align:middle line:90%
So this is the Linnik theorem.

00:51:49.165 --> 00:51:59.535 align:middle line:90%


00:51:59.535 --> 00:52:00.035 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:00.035 --> 00:52:05.350 align:middle line:90%


00:52:05.350 --> 00:52:05.850 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:52:05.850 --> 00:52:13.500 align:middle line:90%


00:52:13.500 --> 00:52:14.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:14.500 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:17.210 align:middle line:90%
Let me mention in this picture.

00:52:17.210 --> 00:52:19.550 align:middle line:84%
So we had this theme that
if you take one function

00:52:19.550 --> 00:52:23.150 align:middle line:84%
and you reduce it mod p for many
different p's, then most of them

00:52:23.150 --> 00:52:24.950 align:middle line:90%
are almost constant.

00:52:24.950 --> 00:52:28.100 align:middle line:84%
So why the constant
frequency is special

00:52:28.100 --> 00:52:30.655 align:middle line:84%
compared to all the other
frequencies in this story.

00:52:30.655 --> 00:52:34.175 align:middle line:90%


00:52:34.175 --> 00:52:34.675 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:34.675 --> 00:52:41.870 align:middle line:90%


00:52:41.870 --> 00:52:45.330 align:middle line:84%
So let me shade in for
one particular prime,

00:52:45.330 --> 00:52:48.770 align:middle line:90%
the frequency is alpha over p.

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:54.985 align:middle line:84%
So that would be frequencies
alpha over P1 alpha and z P1.

00:52:54.985 --> 00:52:59.000 align:middle line:90%


00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:00.505 align:middle line:90%
Let me do it for another prime.

00:53:00.505 --> 00:53:07.000 align:middle line:90%


00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:10.790 align:middle line:84%
In the color blue, I'll
draw alpha over P2,

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:14.660 align:middle line:90%
alpha in Z mod P2.

00:53:14.660 --> 00:53:16.910 align:middle line:90%
What would that look like?

00:53:16.910 --> 00:53:21.410 align:middle line:84%
Well, crucially, it
would still have zero

00:53:21.410 --> 00:53:23.760 align:middle line:84%
but all the other ones
would be different.

00:53:23.760 --> 00:53:30.410 align:middle line:90%


00:53:30.410 --> 00:53:31.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:31.440 --> 00:53:33.950 align:middle line:84%
So now imagine doing this
with all the different primes

00:53:33.950 --> 00:53:38.870 align:middle line:84%
in our set of primes P sub M.
I would get a whole rainbow

00:53:38.870 --> 00:53:40.250 align:middle line:90%
of different stuff.

00:53:40.250 --> 00:53:44.150 align:middle line:84%
Zero would be in every
color, but other than that,

00:53:44.150 --> 00:53:45.600 align:middle line:90%
each point is only one color.

00:53:45.600 --> 00:53:46.767 align:middle line:90%
There are no other overlaps.

00:53:46.767 --> 00:53:49.430 align:middle line:90%


00:53:49.430 --> 00:53:49.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:49.930 --> 00:53:53.103 align:middle line:84%
Now, f hat can be
distributed anyway.

00:53:53.103 --> 00:53:54.770 align:middle line:84%
We've assumed nothing
about the function

00:53:54.770 --> 00:53:57.140 align:middle line:84%
f, except that it's
supported from 1 to n.

00:53:57.140 --> 00:53:58.880 align:middle line:84%
So we know nothing
about its Fourier

00:53:58.880 --> 00:54:02.390 align:middle line:84%
transform except
for this heuristic.

00:54:02.390 --> 00:54:08.120 align:middle line:84%
So f hat could look
like anything, but--

00:54:08.120 --> 00:54:11.630 align:middle line:84%
well, most of the places
that you put f hat--

00:54:11.630 --> 00:54:13.490 align:middle line:84%
OK, so one thing
we do know is let's

00:54:13.490 --> 00:54:16.190 align:middle line:84%
say we know the sum of
f-- the L2 norm of f.

00:54:16.190 --> 00:54:18.950 align:middle line:90%
So we know the L2 norm of f hat.

00:54:18.950 --> 00:54:24.000 align:middle line:84%
If you stick some mass of L2
norm of f hat over this point,

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:27.950 align:middle line:84%
it will contribute to this one
prime, but none of the others.

00:54:27.950 --> 00:54:30.420 align:middle line:84%
But if you stick
some mass over zero,

00:54:30.420 --> 00:54:33.560 align:middle line:90%
it will contribute to everybody.

00:54:33.560 --> 00:54:36.530 align:middle line:84%
So zero frequency is being
counted very differently

00:54:36.530 --> 00:54:37.950 align:middle line:90%
from any other frequency.

00:54:37.950 --> 00:54:40.980 align:middle line:84%
Every other frequency only
contributes to one prime,

00:54:40.980 --> 00:54:43.330 align:middle line:84%
but the zero frequency
contributes to all primes.

00:54:43.330 --> 00:54:46.910 align:middle line:90%


00:54:46.910 --> 00:54:49.440 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, if I start
with my function f,

00:54:49.440 --> 00:54:52.710 align:middle line:84%
if it has a decent amount
in the zero frequency,

00:54:52.710 --> 00:54:55.490 align:middle line:84%
then all the different p's
also will see a decent amount

00:54:55.490 --> 00:54:57.410 align:middle line:90%
in the zero frequency.

00:54:57.410 --> 00:55:00.240 align:middle line:84%
And then my function may have
a bunch of other frequencies,

00:55:00.240 --> 00:55:05.310 align:middle line:84%
but each one of them is only
contributing to one prime.

00:55:05.310 --> 00:55:06.960 align:middle line:84%
If I average over
all the primes,

00:55:06.960 --> 00:55:11.720 align:middle line:84%
those get damped down a lot
compared to the zero frequency.

00:55:11.720 --> 00:55:15.962 align:middle line:84%
So that's what's going--
that's a possible intuition

00:55:15.962 --> 00:55:17.670 align:middle line:84%
about what's going on
in the large sieve.

00:55:17.670 --> 00:55:21.000 align:middle line:90%


00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:21.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:21.500 --> 00:55:25.745 align:middle line:84%
So the last thing to round out
our proof of the large sieve

00:55:25.745 --> 00:55:30.530 align:middle line:84%
is we'll actually rigorously
prove this heuristic.

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:32.815 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
before we do that?

00:55:32.815 --> 00:55:40.520 align:middle line:90%


00:55:40.520 --> 00:55:44.480 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Well, it seems like
we have more freedom to choose f

00:55:44.480 --> 00:55:49.100 align:middle line:90%
here than in the real sieve.

00:55:49.100 --> 00:55:51.500 align:middle line:84%
We always just
choose [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:51.500 --> 00:55:55.587 align:middle line:90%


00:55:55.587 --> 00:55:56.420 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:55:56.420 --> 00:55:59.240 align:middle line:84%
So the question
is, do we choose f?

00:55:59.240 --> 00:56:01.790 align:middle line:84%
So here, f doesn't have to be
the characteristic function

00:56:01.790 --> 00:56:02.490 align:middle line:90%
a set.

00:56:02.490 --> 00:56:05.000 align:middle line:84%
We've often talked about f being
the characteristic function

00:56:05.000 --> 00:56:05.970 align:middle line:90%
of a set.

00:56:05.970 --> 00:56:07.060 align:middle line:90%
What's up with that?

00:56:07.060 --> 00:56:09.590 align:middle line:90%


00:56:09.590 --> 00:56:11.658 align:middle line:84%
We'll also do something
at the end of class,

00:56:11.658 --> 00:56:13.450 align:middle line:84%
we'll mention something
in the real setting

00:56:13.450 --> 00:56:15.930 align:middle line:84%
where f doesn't have to be
a characteristic function.

00:56:15.930 --> 00:56:22.360 align:middle line:90%


00:56:22.360 --> 00:56:22.970 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:56:22.970 --> 00:56:26.230 align:middle line:84%
So there are some theorems
that become interesting

00:56:26.230 --> 00:56:29.720 align:middle line:84%
where f is a characteristic
function of a sparse set,

00:56:29.720 --> 00:56:32.183 align:middle line:84%
and that sparsity
comes into play.

00:56:32.183 --> 00:56:34.350 align:middle line:84%
And there are others where
f could just be anything.

00:56:34.350 --> 00:56:37.810 align:middle line:90%


00:56:37.810 --> 00:56:39.315 align:middle line:90%
They're all part of the theory.

00:56:39.315 --> 00:56:43.930 align:middle line:90%


00:56:43.930 --> 00:56:44.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:44.430 --> 00:57:10.600 align:middle line:90%


00:57:10.600 --> 00:57:13.237 align:middle line:84%
This heuristic, this
locally constant heuristic

00:57:13.237 --> 00:57:15.070 align:middle line:84%
is similar to the one
that's on the homework

00:57:15.070 --> 00:57:17.070 align:middle line:84%
that you're thinking
through that's due tonight.

00:57:17.070 --> 00:57:18.760 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, there
are office hours

00:57:18.760 --> 00:57:20.302 align:middle line:84%
after the class for
anybody who would

00:57:20.302 --> 00:57:24.460 align:middle line:84%
like to talk about
that or anything else.

00:57:24.460 --> 00:57:25.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:57:25.100 --> 00:57:29.740 align:middle line:84%
So I'll also prove this
in class, and yeah.

00:57:29.740 --> 00:57:31.330 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:57:31.330 --> 00:57:33.790 align:middle line:90%
So how does it work?

00:57:33.790 --> 00:57:38.590 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to choose a function
psi N, a function Z to C

00:57:38.590 --> 00:57:45.970 align:middle line:84%
so that psi N of little n is 1
if N is an integer from 1 to N.

00:57:45.970 --> 00:57:50.183 align:middle line:84%
And psi N is also smooth
and rapidly decaying.

00:57:50.183 --> 00:57:58.930 align:middle line:90%


00:57:58.930 --> 00:58:01.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:01.130 --> 00:58:04.600 align:middle line:84%
So then when I take the
Fourier transform of psi N,

00:58:04.600 --> 00:58:07.930 align:middle line:90%
it behaves like this.

00:58:07.930 --> 00:58:11.590 align:middle line:84%
So it's around N
if the frequency

00:58:11.590 --> 00:58:17.595 align:middle line:84%
ksi has size less than 1 over N,
and then it's rapidly decaying.

00:58:17.595 --> 00:58:20.350 align:middle line:90%


00:58:20.350 --> 00:58:24.740 align:middle line:84%
So in pictures-- so ksi is
only well-defined modulo 1.

00:58:24.740 --> 00:58:28.450 align:middle line:84%
And in this context, it's nice
to draw the modulo 1 is going

00:58:28.450 --> 00:58:31.365 align:middle line:84%
from negative 1/2
to positive 1/2, 0.

00:58:31.365 --> 00:58:35.290 align:middle line:90%


00:58:35.290 --> 00:58:40.120 align:middle line:84%
So this axis has the
norm of psi N hat of ksi.

00:58:40.120 --> 00:58:42.580 align:middle line:84%
This is N, and
this distance here

00:58:42.580 --> 00:58:46.980 align:middle line:84%
is 1 over N. That's
what it looks like.

00:58:46.980 --> 00:58:47.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:47.480 --> 00:58:55.220 align:middle line:84%
And rapidly decaying could mean
rigorously N times ksi times N.

00:58:55.220 --> 00:58:57.170 align:middle line:84%
So once ksi is
bigger than 1 over N,

00:58:57.170 --> 00:59:00.190 align:middle line:84%
this thing starts to be
bigger than 1 and kick in.

00:59:00.190 --> 00:59:01.780 align:middle line:90%
You could throw in that.

00:59:01.780 --> 00:59:02.445 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:59:02.445 --> 00:59:03.820 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So what
does smoothness

00:59:03.820 --> 00:59:06.337 align:middle line:84%
mean for a map
from the integers?

00:59:06.337 --> 00:59:07.170 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:59:07.170 --> 00:59:08.405 align:middle line:90%
What does smoothness mean?

00:59:08.405 --> 00:59:11.670 align:middle line:90%


00:59:11.670 --> 00:59:13.041 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:59:13.041 --> 00:59:15.210 align:middle line:84%
You could think of
psi as a map that's

00:59:15.210 --> 00:59:17.250 align:middle line:84%
defined on the whole
real line, and it's

00:59:17.250 --> 00:59:19.080 align:middle line:84%
smooth on the whole
real line, and then

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:22.634 align:middle line:84%
we happen to be evaluating
it at the integers.

00:59:22.634 --> 00:59:23.134 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:59:23.134 --> 00:59:29.425 align:middle line:90%


00:59:29.425 --> 00:59:29.925 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:29.925 --> 00:59:36.660 align:middle line:90%


00:59:36.660 --> 00:59:39.390 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:59:39.390 --> 00:59:40.090 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:40.090 --> 00:59:48.990 align:middle line:84%
Now this is helpful because
f is equal to f times psi N.

00:59:48.990 --> 00:59:55.500 align:middle line:84%
So if the support of f is
contained in integers f to N.

00:59:55.500 --> 00:59:57.490 align:middle line:84%
And then when we take
the Fourier transform,

00:59:57.490 --> 01:00:03.450 align:middle line:84%
we get that f hat is f hat
convolved with psi N hat.

01:00:03.450 --> 01:00:11.220 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular, so f hat
at a particular frequency of ksi

01:00:11.220 --> 01:00:14.640 align:middle line:84%
is f hat convolved
with psi N hat.

01:00:14.640 --> 01:00:17.430 align:middle line:90%
Psi N hat looks like that.

01:00:17.430 --> 01:00:22.890 align:middle line:84%
So the norm of f hat is bounded
by the norm of f hat convolved

01:00:22.890 --> 01:00:27.870 align:middle line:84%
with psi N hat, and also
the norm of f hat squared

01:00:27.870 --> 01:00:32.100 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the norm of f hat
squared convolved with psi N

01:00:32.100 --> 01:00:36.180 align:middle line:90%
hat by Cauchy-Schwarz.

01:00:36.180 --> 01:00:38.490 align:middle line:84%
So actually one
feature of this formula

01:00:38.490 --> 01:00:44.230 align:middle line:84%
is that the integral of psi
N hat ksi is bounded by 1.

01:00:44.230 --> 01:00:54.540 align:middle line:90%


01:00:54.540 --> 01:00:56.650 align:middle line:84%
It has height 1
and it has width--

01:00:56.650 --> 01:00:58.415 align:middle line:90%
height n and width 1 over n.

01:00:58.415 --> 01:01:02.220 align:middle line:90%


01:01:02.220 --> 01:01:02.920 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:06.210 align:middle line:84%
So psi n hat is the
Fourier transform

01:01:06.210 --> 01:01:10.280 align:middle line:84%
of cosine in the sense
of real function?

01:01:10.280 --> 01:01:12.840 align:middle line:90%


01:01:12.840 --> 01:01:16.850 align:middle line:84%
Or it is a reference
point in the sense of--

01:01:16.850 --> 01:01:19.830 align:middle line:90%


01:01:19.830 --> 01:01:20.580 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

01:01:20.580 --> 01:01:20.950 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:01:20.950 --> 01:01:21.790 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

01:01:21.790 --> 01:01:22.660 align:middle line:90%
That's a good question.

01:01:22.660 --> 01:01:23.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:23.160 --> 01:01:25.980 align:middle line:90%


01:01:25.980 --> 01:01:28.380 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:01:28.380 --> 01:01:32.010 align:middle line:84%
So phi, I had originally said,
is a function on the integers.

01:01:32.010 --> 01:01:35.363 align:middle line:84%
But in answer to the question,
what does it mean to be smooth?

01:01:35.363 --> 01:01:36.780 align:middle line:84%
I said, we should
also think of it

01:01:36.780 --> 01:01:39.250 align:middle line:90%
as a function on the real line.

01:01:39.250 --> 01:01:43.230 align:middle line:84%
So I'll call them
psi n integers.

01:01:43.230 --> 01:01:45.240 align:middle line:84%
That's our function
on the integers.

01:01:45.240 --> 01:01:47.100 align:middle line:90%
Psi N real line.

01:01:47.100 --> 01:01:50.220 align:middle line:84%
That's a function
on the real line.

01:01:50.220 --> 01:01:53.160 align:middle line:84%
And they each have
a Fourier transform.

01:01:53.160 --> 01:01:57.330 align:middle line:84%
Psi n on the integers
hat of ksi is

01:01:57.330 --> 01:02:04.890 align:middle line:84%
the sum over integers psi n of
n, e to the minus 2 pi i n ksi.

01:02:04.890 --> 01:02:08.980 align:middle line:84%
And psi n, if you think of
it as a real valued function,

01:02:08.980 --> 01:02:10.320 align:middle line:90%
it has a Fourier transform.

01:02:10.320 --> 01:02:15.630 align:middle line:84%
And ksi, that's defined to be
the integral over the real line.

01:02:15.630 --> 01:02:20.955 align:middle line:84%
Psi n of x, e to the
minus 2 pi i x ksi dx.

01:02:20.955 --> 01:02:23.910 align:middle line:90%


01:02:23.910 --> 01:02:24.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:24.520 --> 01:02:28.740 align:middle line:84%
So the question was, when I
write psi n hat, which one

01:02:28.740 --> 01:02:31.590 align:middle line:90%
of these two things do I mean?

01:02:31.590 --> 01:02:32.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:32.290 --> 01:02:36.690 align:middle line:84%
So I mean this one, but
they're equal to each other.

01:02:36.690 --> 01:02:43.860 align:middle line:84%
So the Poisson
summation theorem says

01:02:43.860 --> 01:02:49.860 align:middle line:90%
that psi n z hat is equal to--

01:02:49.860 --> 01:02:52.050 align:middle line:90%
oops.

01:02:52.050 --> 01:02:53.240 align:middle line:90%
Is equal to.

01:02:53.240 --> 01:02:56.370 align:middle line:90%


01:02:56.370 --> 01:02:57.210 align:middle line:90%
Is that right?

01:02:57.210 --> 01:02:59.850 align:middle line:90%


01:02:59.850 --> 01:03:01.380 align:middle line:90%
Wait, wait, wait.

01:03:01.380 --> 01:03:03.872 align:middle line:90%
So these are closely related.

01:03:03.872 --> 01:03:04.955 align:middle line:90%
Let me think for a second.

01:03:04.955 --> 01:03:17.130 align:middle line:90%


01:03:17.130 --> 01:03:17.850 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:03:17.850 --> 01:03:31.900 align:middle line:84%
So this guy is the sum of z in
z of psi n R hat of ksi plus z.

01:03:31.900 --> 01:03:37.813 align:middle line:90%


01:03:37.813 --> 01:03:38.313 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:38.313 --> 01:03:41.211 align:middle line:90%


01:03:41.211 --> 01:03:42.845 align:middle line:90%
So we should make two pictures.

01:03:42.845 --> 01:03:47.640 align:middle line:90%


01:03:47.640 --> 01:03:54.840 align:middle line:84%
In yellow, I will
draw psi n R hat of z.

01:03:54.840 --> 01:03:56.245 align:middle line:90%
And let's extend this.

01:03:56.245 --> 01:03:59.630 align:middle line:90%


01:03:59.630 --> 01:04:02.450 align:middle line:90%
It looks basically the same.

01:04:02.450 --> 01:04:08.815 align:middle line:84%
And then it gets really small
and it stays really small.

01:04:08.815 --> 01:04:11.840 align:middle line:90%


01:04:11.840 --> 01:04:19.850 align:middle line:84%
And what does-- so in blue,
I'll do psi n z hat ksi.

01:04:19.850 --> 01:04:23.150 align:middle line:90%


01:04:23.150 --> 01:04:31.530 align:middle line:84%
It looks really almost the same
except this one is periodic.

01:04:31.530 --> 01:04:34.020 align:middle line:84%
This Fourier transform
is defined on R modulo z,

01:04:34.020 --> 01:04:36.020 align:middle line:90%
so it's going to be periodic.

01:04:36.020 --> 01:04:36.960 align:middle line:90%
Z periodic.

01:04:36.960 --> 01:04:42.620 align:middle line:84%
So then here at minus 1,
it's going to go up again.

01:04:42.620 --> 01:04:44.420 align:middle line:84%
There's going to be
an identical copy.

01:04:44.420 --> 01:04:45.613 align:middle line:90%
The blue one is z periodic.

01:04:45.613 --> 01:04:55.070 align:middle line:90%


01:04:55.070 --> 01:04:56.966 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:56.966 --> 01:04:58.800 align:middle line:90%
So if you compare.

01:04:58.800 --> 01:05:01.400 align:middle line:84%
So then if you look
at this formula,

01:05:01.400 --> 01:05:03.890 align:middle line:84%
also, it's taking this
function and turning it

01:05:03.890 --> 01:05:07.280 align:middle line:84%
into a z periodic function
by periodizing it.

01:05:07.280 --> 01:05:10.340 align:middle line:84%
And since this function
originally was extremely

01:05:10.340 --> 01:05:12.870 align:middle line:84%
localized to between
minus 1/2 and 1/2,

01:05:12.870 --> 01:05:16.430 align:middle line:84%
it almost looks like I took the
yellow function and I just took

01:05:16.430 --> 01:05:19.910 align:middle line:90%
copies of it and put them here.

01:05:19.910 --> 01:05:24.860 align:middle line:90%
So the copy over here can--

01:05:24.860 --> 01:05:25.460 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:05:25.460 --> 01:05:25.960 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:05:25.960 --> 01:05:27.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:27.680 --> 01:05:29.658 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so that's
what this one--

01:05:29.658 --> 01:05:32.200 align:middle line:84%
that's what this one looks like
and what this one looks like.

01:05:32.200 --> 01:05:37.400 align:middle line:90%


01:05:37.400 --> 01:05:39.575 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:39.575 --> 01:05:42.320 align:middle line:84%
So to prove this
estimate, first you

01:05:42.320 --> 01:05:46.400 align:middle line:84%
prove it for psi n R. And
you can do that using Fourier

01:05:46.400 --> 01:05:49.010 align:middle line:84%
analysis over R. And
you use the smoothness

01:05:49.010 --> 01:05:51.770 align:middle line:84%
and you integrate
by parts many times.

01:05:51.770 --> 01:05:56.340 align:middle line:84%
And then to study the 1 over
z, you use this formula.

01:05:56.340 --> 01:05:59.340 align:middle line:84%
And because this guy
is decaying so rapidly,

01:05:59.340 --> 01:06:04.490 align:middle line:84%
the contribution from the-- so
if this ksi is between minus one

01:06:04.490 --> 01:06:07.130 align:middle line:84%
half and one half,
then the contribution

01:06:07.130 --> 01:06:12.800 align:middle line:84%
coming from integers z other
than 0 is incredibly small.

01:06:12.800 --> 01:06:13.370 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

01:06:13.370 --> 01:06:14.870 align:middle line:84%
So using the bounds
for this one you

01:06:14.870 --> 01:06:16.440 align:middle line:90%
use to give bounds for this one.

01:06:16.440 --> 01:06:23.490 align:middle line:90%


01:06:23.490 --> 01:06:23.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:23.990 --> 01:06:25.350 align:middle line:84%
Thanks for those
questions, everybody.

01:06:25.350 --> 01:06:26.058 align:middle line:90%
That was helpful.

01:06:26.058 --> 01:07:01.080 align:middle line:90%


01:07:01.080 --> 01:07:04.430 align:middle line:84%
So now we're going to do a
slightly more rigorous version

01:07:04.430 --> 01:07:05.395 align:middle line:90%
of this argument.

01:07:05.395 --> 01:07:10.700 align:middle line:90%


01:07:10.700 --> 01:07:12.130 align:middle line:90%
So rigorous proof.

01:07:12.130 --> 01:07:15.890 align:middle line:90%


01:07:15.890 --> 01:07:18.680 align:middle line:84%
So the left-hand
side, we decided,

01:07:18.680 --> 01:07:22.340 align:middle line:84%
was around 1 over
M times the sum

01:07:22.340 --> 01:07:30.600 align:middle line:84%
over the frequencies in QM of
f high hat ksi norm squared.

01:07:30.600 --> 01:07:32.270 align:middle line:90%
That part was rigorous before.

01:07:32.270 --> 01:07:33.960 align:middle line:84%
We didn't need to
make it rigorous.

01:07:33.960 --> 01:07:37.190 align:middle line:84%
But now we need to relate
this sum to an integral.

01:07:37.190 --> 01:07:40.980 align:middle line:90%
And we use this fact here.

01:07:40.980 --> 01:07:44.180 align:middle line:84%
This fact encodes the idea
that this quantity is locally

01:07:44.180 --> 01:07:50.230 align:middle line:84%
constant at the scale
1 over N. So this

01:07:50.230 --> 01:07:57.130 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by 1
over M sum ksi in QM

01:07:57.130 --> 01:08:06.610 align:middle line:84%
of the integral f hat
squared of omega times psi n

01:08:06.610 --> 01:08:11.150 align:middle line:90%
hat of ksi minus omega d omega.

01:08:11.150 --> 01:08:13.690 align:middle line:90%


01:08:13.690 --> 01:08:17.200 align:middle line:84%
So this is just writing out
the convolution as an integral.

01:08:17.200 --> 01:08:20.830 align:middle line:84%
Now we can bring
this sum inside.

01:08:20.830 --> 01:08:26.600 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1 over M
integral f high hat

01:08:26.600 --> 01:08:30.640 align:middle line:84%
of omega squared
times the sum over ksi

01:08:30.640 --> 01:08:38.460 align:middle line:84%
in QM of psi n hat of
ksi minus omega d omega.

01:08:38.460 --> 01:08:42.069 align:middle line:90%


01:08:42.069 --> 01:08:42.833 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:42.833 --> 01:08:48.580 align:middle line:84%
And this sum we can
bound by N. Why?

01:08:48.580 --> 01:08:52.660 align:middle line:84%
Because each term in the sum
has size at least around N.

01:08:52.660 --> 01:08:57.100 align:middle line:84%
This term is a bump, essentially
a bump of height N and width 1

01:08:57.100 --> 01:08:59.170 align:middle line:90%
over N around ksi.

01:08:59.170 --> 01:09:02.920 align:middle line:84%
And the distance between any two
different ksi's is at least 1

01:09:02.920 --> 01:09:07.210 align:middle line:84%
over N, so those bumps don't
overlap with each other.

01:09:07.210 --> 01:09:09.890 align:middle line:84%
Now, the bumps aren't
quite compactly supported.

01:09:09.890 --> 01:09:12.620 align:middle line:84%
They have the tails that
you can see in the picture,

01:09:12.620 --> 01:09:14.600 align:middle line:84%
but the tails are
incredibly tiny.

01:09:14.600 --> 01:09:17.180 align:middle line:84%
And so if you just plug in
the rapidly decaying bound,

01:09:17.180 --> 01:09:19.965 align:middle line:84%
the tails don't contribute
anything and you get this bound.

01:09:19.965 --> 01:09:25.930 align:middle line:90%


01:09:25.930 --> 01:09:26.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:26.510 --> 01:09:30.310 align:middle line:84%
Then if you take out this n,
you have what we had before.

01:09:30.310 --> 01:09:36.234 align:middle line:84%
N over M, integral from 0 to
1, f high hat squared ksi,

01:09:36.234 --> 01:09:45.880 align:middle line:84%
ksi, N over M sum f
high of N norm squared.

01:09:45.880 --> 01:09:48.885 align:middle line:84%
And that's the proof of
Linnik's large sieve.

01:09:48.885 --> 01:10:26.190 align:middle line:90%


01:10:26.190 --> 01:10:26.690 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:10:26.690 --> 01:10:29.375 align:middle line:84%
So we only have a little bit of
time left, about five minutes.

01:10:29.375 --> 01:10:34.007 align:middle line:90%


01:10:34.007 --> 01:10:35.590 align:middle line:84%
We could either, if
people have things

01:10:35.590 --> 01:10:38.980 align:middle line:84%
you want to talk about we could
just talk for five minutes.

01:10:38.980 --> 01:10:42.100 align:middle line:84%
Or I could set up the
next thing and try

01:10:42.100 --> 01:10:45.250 align:middle line:84%
to give a feeling
of how something

01:10:45.250 --> 01:10:48.040 align:middle line:84%
in real variable setting
is analogous to this thing

01:10:48.040 --> 01:10:49.965 align:middle line:90%
in a number theoretic setting.

01:10:49.965 --> 01:11:04.630 align:middle line:90%


01:11:04.630 --> 01:11:05.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:05.210 --> 01:11:06.760 align:middle line:90%
So I could give a little--

01:11:06.760 --> 01:11:09.490 align:middle line:84%
try to give a little
teaser, preview,

01:11:09.490 --> 01:11:13.670 align:middle line:84%
foreshadowing of how this same
idea occurs in real analysis.

01:11:13.670 --> 01:11:14.865 align:middle line:90%
I want to keep this picture.

01:11:14.865 --> 01:11:36.580 align:middle line:90%


01:11:36.580 --> 01:11:38.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:38.530 --> 01:11:40.180 align:middle line:84%
The thing that we
proved is if you

01:11:40.180 --> 01:11:43.180 align:middle line:84%
have a function on the
integers from 1 to N,

01:11:43.180 --> 01:11:48.160 align:middle line:84%
then when you project it mod
p, most of the projections

01:11:48.160 --> 01:11:49.940 align:middle line:90%
look almost constant.

01:11:49.940 --> 01:11:52.930 align:middle line:84%
They look smoother than
the original function.

01:11:52.930 --> 01:11:56.180 align:middle line:84%
And there's a totally analogous
phenomenon in R to the D.

01:11:56.180 --> 01:11:57.730 align:middle line:84%
If you have a
function on R to the D

01:11:57.730 --> 01:11:59.740 align:middle line:84%
and you consider
projections onto lower

01:11:59.740 --> 01:12:02.500 align:middle line:84%
dimensional subspaces,
then almost all of them

01:12:02.500 --> 01:12:04.970 align:middle line:84%
look smoother than
the original function.

01:12:04.970 --> 01:12:06.650 align:middle line:84%
And like we mentioned
on the first day,

01:12:06.650 --> 01:12:08.180 align:middle line:84%
if you're in high
enough dimension,

01:12:08.180 --> 01:12:13.310 align:middle line:84%
if you take a function and you
project it onto a typical line,

01:12:13.310 --> 01:12:15.610 align:middle line:84%
even if the initial
function is only in L2

01:12:15.610 --> 01:12:19.550 align:middle line:84%
and is nowhere continuous,
on a typical line,

01:12:19.550 --> 01:12:22.360 align:middle line:84%
the projection will be
continuous and even C1

01:12:22.360 --> 01:12:23.950 align:middle line:90%
and even C2.

01:12:23.950 --> 01:12:25.630 align:middle line:84%
So the projections
are much smoother

01:12:25.630 --> 01:12:28.060 align:middle line:90%
than the original function.

01:12:28.060 --> 01:12:29.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:29.080 --> 01:12:32.140 align:middle line:84%
So here is a setup
for this that's

01:12:32.140 --> 01:12:34.510 align:middle line:84%
kind of analogous
to the large sieve.

01:12:34.510 --> 01:12:39.300 align:middle line:84%
So we have a function
on R to the D,

01:12:39.300 --> 01:12:42.000 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll have
v contained in R

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:43.303 align:middle line:90%
to the D which is a subspace.

01:12:43.303 --> 01:12:47.280 align:middle line:90%


01:12:47.280 --> 01:12:53.190 align:middle line:84%
And if you have a function-- so
pi V of f is the projection of f

01:12:53.190 --> 01:12:54.460 align:middle line:90%
onto this plane.

01:12:54.460 --> 01:12:59.290 align:middle line:84%
So that's a function
from V to C.

01:12:59.290 --> 01:12:59.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:59.790 --> 01:13:03.030 align:middle line:84%
So now I have a
remark that if you

01:13:03.030 --> 01:13:07.350 align:middle line:84%
have any function of
this vector space V, then

01:13:07.350 --> 01:13:13.260 align:middle line:84%
its Fourier transform is also
defined on the vector space V.

01:13:13.260 --> 01:13:14.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:14.280 --> 01:13:16.130 align:middle line:90%
And there's a dictionary lemma.

01:13:16.130 --> 01:13:21.690 align:middle line:90%


01:13:21.690 --> 01:13:24.480 align:middle line:84%
How is the Fourier
transform of the projection

01:13:24.480 --> 01:13:28.980 align:middle line:84%
related to the Fourier transform
of the original function?

01:13:28.980 --> 01:13:44.760 align:middle line:84%
And it says that pi V of f hat
is just f hat restricted to V.

01:13:44.760 --> 01:13:46.860 align:middle line:84%
So this is a function
on the vector space

01:13:46.860 --> 01:13:48.390 align:middle line:84%
V. Its Fourier
transform is supposed

01:13:48.390 --> 01:13:49.890 align:middle line:84%
to be a function
on the vector space

01:13:49.890 --> 01:13:55.440 align:middle line:84%
V. f hat is a function
on R to the D.

01:13:55.440 --> 01:13:59.460 align:middle line:84%
But this Fourier transform is
just f hat restricted to that,

01:13:59.460 --> 01:14:02.980 align:middle line:90%
to V. OK.

01:14:02.980 --> 01:14:04.775 align:middle line:90%
So now make a picture.

01:14:04.775 --> 01:14:09.300 align:middle line:90%


01:14:09.300 --> 01:14:14.580 align:middle line:84%
So here is R to the D,
and inside of there,

01:14:14.580 --> 01:14:21.780 align:middle line:84%
there's the space V1 and
there's another space V2.

01:14:21.780 --> 01:14:23.240 align:middle line:90%
Whoops.

01:14:23.240 --> 01:14:23.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:23.740 --> 01:14:25.390 align:middle line:84%
And I let you
imagine other ones.

01:14:25.390 --> 01:14:26.957 align:middle line:84%
They're all
subspaces, so they all

01:14:26.957 --> 01:14:29.165 align:middle line:84%
go through zero, although
my picture was not perfect.

01:14:29.165 --> 01:14:32.700 align:middle line:90%


01:14:32.700 --> 01:14:35.450 align:middle line:84%
And I want you to imagine
this as Fourier space.

01:14:35.450 --> 01:14:40.080 align:middle line:90%


01:14:40.080 --> 01:14:44.190 align:middle line:84%
So we have a function
f. f is just in L2.

01:14:44.190 --> 01:14:46.770 align:middle line:84%
Say it's an L2 function
on the unit ball.

01:14:46.770 --> 01:14:51.990 align:middle line:84%
So its Fourier transform
could be anywhere here.

01:14:51.990 --> 01:14:54.000 align:middle line:84%
And all we know
about it is say we

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:57.810 align:middle line:84%
know the L2 norm of f, so we
know the L2 norm of f hat.

01:14:57.810 --> 01:14:59.340 align:middle line:90%
Could be anywhere.

01:14:59.340 --> 01:15:03.540 align:middle line:84%
If you happen to put some
L2 norm of f hat near 0,

01:15:03.540 --> 01:15:07.170 align:middle line:84%
then that will be part of
the Fourier transform of pi V

01:15:07.170 --> 01:15:10.140 align:middle line:90%
for all the different V's.

01:15:10.140 --> 01:15:14.620 align:middle line:84%
But if you put some of the
L2 mass of f hat over here,

01:15:14.620 --> 01:15:19.800 align:middle line:84%
that will contribute to pi V1,
but it won't contribute to most

01:15:19.800 --> 01:15:20.900 align:middle line:90%
of the other pi V's.

01:15:20.900 --> 01:15:25.080 align:middle line:90%


01:15:25.080 --> 01:15:29.710 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, when you
take a random projection,

01:15:29.710 --> 01:15:32.850 align:middle line:84%
the part of the Fourier
transform at low frequencies

01:15:32.850 --> 01:15:37.800 align:middle line:84%
is more highly represented and
the part at high frequencies

01:15:37.800 --> 01:15:41.010 align:middle line:90%
is less highly represented.

01:15:41.010 --> 01:15:42.653 align:middle line:90%
So a typical projection.

01:15:42.653 --> 01:15:44.070 align:middle line:84%
So initially the
Fourier transform

01:15:44.070 --> 01:15:47.820 align:middle line:84%
could have been anywhere,
but then a typical projection

01:15:47.820 --> 01:15:49.680 align:middle line:84%
will now have its
Fourier transform

01:15:49.680 --> 01:15:53.210 align:middle line:84%
concentrated at low frequencies,
which makes it look smooth.

01:15:53.210 --> 01:15:55.930 align:middle line:90%


01:15:55.930 --> 01:15:56.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:56.430 --> 01:15:58.055 align:middle line:84%
So here's a statement
like that that we

01:15:58.055 --> 01:16:04.410 align:middle line:84%
will prove next time by the
analogous reasoning theorem.

01:16:04.410 --> 01:16:09.090 align:middle line:84%
If f is an L2 function on R
to the D supported in the unit

01:16:09.090 --> 01:16:22.750 align:middle line:84%
ball, and if D is big enough,
then for almost every--

01:16:22.750 --> 01:16:28.530 align:middle line:84%
so then if I take the
average over theta in the D

01:16:28.530 --> 01:16:34.920 align:middle line:90%
minus 1 sphere of pi theta of f.

01:16:34.920 --> 01:16:37.010 align:middle line:84%
So this means I take
f and I project it

01:16:37.010 --> 01:16:40.810 align:middle line:84%
onto the line in
the theta direction.

01:16:40.810 --> 01:16:44.860 align:middle line:84%
CK norm of that is bounded
by the L2 norm of f.

01:16:44.860 --> 01:17:02.600 align:middle line:90%


01:17:02.600 --> 01:17:05.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:05.320 --> 01:17:06.570 align:middle line:90%
So we'll prove that next time.

01:17:06.570 --> 01:17:09.290 align:middle line:84%
But to end, I just
wanted to have

01:17:09.290 --> 01:17:12.350 align:middle line:84%
everyone look at the analogy
between these two pictures.

01:17:12.350 --> 01:17:15.950 align:middle line:84%
So in Fourier space when
we project our function

01:17:15.950 --> 01:17:19.070 align:middle line:84%
onto different
subspaces, then we

01:17:19.070 --> 01:17:21.110 align:middle line:84%
have these different
pieces of the Fourier

01:17:21.110 --> 01:17:22.970 align:middle line:90%
transform that we're seeing.

01:17:22.970 --> 01:17:25.760 align:middle line:84%
And in Fourier space
in the large sieve,

01:17:25.760 --> 01:17:27.680 align:middle line:84%
when we take our
function and we project

01:17:27.680 --> 01:17:30.380 align:middle line:84%
it mod p for different p, we
have these different color

01:17:30.380 --> 01:17:33.620 align:middle line:84%
pieces of the Fourier
space that we're seeing.

01:17:33.620 --> 01:17:38.420 align:middle line:84%
And the different color
pieces intersect at 0,

01:17:38.420 --> 01:17:42.110 align:middle line:84%
and they don't
intersect anywhere else,

01:17:42.110 --> 01:17:45.590 align:middle line:84%
or they don't intersect
very much anywhere else.

01:17:45.590 --> 01:17:48.810 align:middle line:84%
And that has the effect that
when you take the projections,

01:17:48.810 --> 01:17:53.900 align:middle line:84%
it emphasizes the zero
frequency or the low frequency.

01:17:53.900 --> 01:17:56.960 align:middle line:84%
And that plays out slightly
in slightly different ways

01:17:56.960 --> 01:17:59.185 align:middle line:84%
in the different settings
but morally very similar.

01:17:59.185 --> 01:18:09.110 align:middle line:90%


01:18:09.110 --> 01:18:10.970 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:18:10.970 --> 01:18:11.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:11.590 --> 01:18:12.090 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

